We talk about people who self diagnose themselves. Like no, Emily, you do not have four different mental disorders just because you saw a TikTok that said if you breathe sometimes and also blink, you might have ADHD. Congratulations, that's called being a human. Look, I get it. Mental health awareness is hella important. It's amazing that people are talking about it more openly now. But here's the problem scrolling through hashtags at 2:00am is not the same thing as a professional evaluation. Google is not your therapist. ID Labs test are not your psychiatrist. And that one influencer who talks about their symptoms in a story time? Definitely not a doctor. When everyone just casually slaps a label on themselves, it waters down the real struggles people actually face. Like someone living with legit OCD is out here battling life every day and then some dude is like oh my god I'm so OCD I color code my closet. No, you're not OCD. You're just organized my guy. And even with depression, just because you're feeling a little sad one week does not mean you have depression. Unless you're diagnosed, I don't want to hear it. You're free to self pity in private, but self diagnosing is probably one of the most selfish and attention seeking things you can do. Faith out.

You ever just realise someone who used to be your whole world is now just someone you used to know? Like no big fallout, no drama, just slowly stop talking, stop checking in, stop being us. And you sit there wondering when it happened. Like what was the moment? What did I miss? How did we go from daily convos and inside jokes to seen and silence? And the worst part, I still care. I still see stuff and think they'd laugh at this or I wish I could tell them this, but I don't cause now it'd feel weird. Sad how people become strangers with memories. Yeah, I could reach out, I could say something, but deep down I know if they wanted to talk to me, they would have. And I'm tired of always being the one holding the glue. So I just sit with it, act like I'm over it, pretend like losing people I never thought I'd lose is normal now. Whatever. People come and go, right? But fuck some of them I really wanted to stay.

Teacher's pet called me an idiot, so I royally screwed him over. I was assigned to work on a project with this kid named Marcus and the first thing he said to me was, I need you to understand something. I scored 1,540 on my SAT's. You scored what? 1,200? So here's what's happening. I'll do all the talking during the presentation because I actually understand the nuances. Okay? So I had to deal with this pretentious douchebag for the next week. Great. He pulled out his phone and started scrolling. Your only job is to write down everything I say for the slides. Every single thing. You are too much of an idiot to think anyway, now here's the thing. This dumb kid had a habit of pausing his sentences to say nasty things about others. Like he just started dictating about the Cold War, but then paused to say, wait, hold on, is that Jessica? Damn, she looks incredible today. Look at those tight jeans. I got a brilliant idea. Open Powerpoint and started typing, figuring I should do exactly what he says. So I transcribed everything he said, even that line about Jessica. In fact, for the next week, Marcus would corner me in the library and dictate while doing literally everything else as I transcribed it all into perfectly formatted slides. Monday's session, the Marshall Plan represented. Damn, did you see Brian's outfit today? Looks like a highlighter threw up on him. Tuesday, I swear, Samantha Keeps staring at me. She's obviously down bad for me. Wednesday. Honestly, if I have to hear Peterson talk about his fake Yale degree one more time, I'll lose it. By Thursday, I had 20 slides filled with all those comments. I asked if he wanted to review what was actually on the slides, his nasty ass comments, but he just said, why would I need to review my own words? Just make sure they auto advance every 45 seconds. I've calculated my pacing perfectly. He was already walking away. Oh, and use Times New Roman, 24 point font, maximum visibility. Okay bro, relax. Downfall is inevitable. The night before our presentation, Marcus texted me at eleven PM you didn't change anything, right? Every word exactly as I said it. I responded every single word exactly as instructed. Good. That's why I picked you as my partner. You actually follow directions unlike the other idiots in class. The following morning he texted again barking orders as usual. Set everything up before class. I'll arrive exactly when the bell rings. My entrance timing is crucial for commanding attention. Then make sure Peterson, our teacher, sees this. He needs to understand what actual historical analysis looks like, not his community college level takes. Just so you know, I wrote down that line as well. Can't wait for Peterson to see that. Any anyway, I set up the laptop projector and made sure the auto advance was enabled. Marcus walked in as the Bell rang, winked at Jessica in the front row, and approached the podium without even looking at me. Marcus clicked the remote with total confidence and began. Ladies and gentlemen, today we'll explore the Cold War's complex dynamics. The first slide seemed normal enough, just the title. He continued smoothly. The origins of this.

Teachers, what was the best smartass response from a student you have heard? I caught Sarah, our valedictorian candidate, with earbuds during finals. Automatic failure. College recommendations revoked. But when I grabbed them, I heard a voice, not music. A live medical consultation. Sarah never broke rules. Harvard bound, 4.0 G P A. Volunteered at homeless shelters. Seeing her cheat was like catching Mother Teresa shoplifting. Her hands were shaking so badly, she couldn't hold the pencil steady. My office now, I whispered. She didn't move. Couldn't move. That's when I noticed the bruises. Fresh ones on her wrist, partially hidden by her sleeve. Please. She mouth silently. Not today. After class, I cornered her. Sarah, those earbuds. It's my little brother, she interrupted, tears streaming. He's 7, type 1 diabetic. Mom works three jobs since dad left. I monitor his glucose levels during school hours because as the nurse at his school, quit. She showed me her phone. Blood sugar dropping dangerously. 52 milligrams per deciliter. Critical low. I talked him through eating his emergency glucose tablets during question 23. If I hadn't, she couldn't finish. Next morning, Assistant Principal Harrison summoned me. Beside him sat Missus Brennan, head of the Honor Council, practically salivating. Sarah Mitchell earbuds during finals, Harrison stated. Missus Brennan witnessed everything through the window. Cheating is cheating, Missus Brennan declared. She'll lose her Harvard admission. Sets an example for others contemplating academic dishonesty. Example? I laughed bitterly. Let me tell you about examples. Sarah Scored 98% on that exam while preventing her brother from going into diabetic coma. She's been his remote caregiver for six months, maintaining perfect grades while essentially being a parent. Irrelevant. Missus Brennan snap!

My parents took me to court for buying a house. Last month I bought my first home after 13 years of grinding. My reward, a court summons from my own parents. The reason? That house should have been sages. I thought they were joking. They weren't. See, I've been living off ramen and working 60 hour weeks since college while my sister Sage got a full ride through life, art school, fancy apartment, everything handed to her when she graduated with her 180K art history degree. My parents promised her they'd help buy a house. Problem is, they're broke. Turns out funding Sage's lifestyle for 26 years drained their savings. when I finally scraped together enough for a down payment on a modest three bedroom, suddenly I became the villain. Their lawyer wanted me to transfer the house to my sister, pay off her mortgage, 50 k for emotional damages and write an apology for breaking up the family. I laughed so hard I snorted then hung up. The harassment started immediately. Mom posted on Facebook, some children forget where they came from. His sister has student loans and no stable housing. A good son would help his family. Disappointed. Now your family values, my aunt commented, shameful behavior. Your sister needs that house more than you need your selfishness. I got uninvited from Thanksgiving. The family group chat explode. Cousins I hadn't talked to in years suddenly had opinions about my greed. My uncle called me selfish for Not stepping up when family needed help. Extended family members I barely knew were messaging me, telling me I was destroying the family and that I should do the right thing. Sage started posting Instagram stories about being betrayed by blood and how money changes people. She, she filmed herself crying outside my new house, talking about how she just wanted a place to call home. My parents escalated. Dad started parking outside my workplace, following me to the grocery store. Mom would show up at my gym, making scenes about how I was breaking her heart. They actually hired a private investigator to go through my finances, trying to prove I somehow stole money or got help from someone. When that turned up nothing, they claimed I must have gotten an illegal loan. Court day arrives. My parents show up with Sage and my aunt, all wearing matching t shirts that said family comes first in giant letters. They brought a photographer to document their fight for justice. The drama started immediately.

Did you realise your parents genuinely didn't see you as human? I had stomach problems my whole childhood. Every single time I felt sick, my mom would roll her eyes and say, you're not dying. Go lie down. My dad would just laugh and tell me she's just trying to get out of chores again. It didn't matter if I was doubled over in pain or throwing up. They always had the same response, stop being dramatic. Take some medicine. You're fine. By the time I was 14, I had Learned to just suffer in silence. There was no point in telling them anything because they never believed me anyway. One night in October, I woke up around midnight with the worst pain I'd ever felt in my life. It was like someone was stabbing me in the stomach with a hot knife. I was sweating so bad, my sheets were soaked and I could barely stand up without shaking. Stumbled to their bedroom door and knocked softly. Mom, Dad, I think something's really wrong. My mom opened the door looking annoyed. She took one look at me standing there in my pajamas, sweating and shaking inside. Layla, it's the middle of the night. Stop being so dramatic and take some pepto. We have work tomorrow. But mom, this feels different. It really hurts and I think I might need to go to the hospital. My dad's voice came from the bed. She's just trying to get attention. Tell her To go back to bed. My mom nodded and started closing the door. You heard your father go lie down and stop waking us up over nothing. I went back to my room and tried to sleep, but the pain kept getting worse. By 2 in the morning, I was throwing up bile and could barely think straight. I tried walking to the bathroom, but halfway down the hallway, everything went black. My little brother Kevin found me collapsed on the floor at 4 in the morning. He was only 8, but he started screaming for our parents when he saw me lying there unconscious. My dad came running out, cursing under his breath, what the hell is wrong with her now? He picked me up and carried me to the car, complaining the entire time about how I was overreacting and.

What's the dumbest reason your mom ever called the school? My mom never called my school. I could have been expelled for arson, and she just say, handle it yourself. So when the principal called me to her office saying, your mother's on the phone, I genuinely thought someone was pranking me. I walked in confused, and the principal handed me the phone with this weird look on her face. Hello? I said. My mom's voice crackled through. Did you eat breakfast this morning? I blinked. What? Breakfast? Did you eat it? I looked at the principal, who was pretending not to listen. Mom, you called this fool to ask if I ate breakfast? Yes, because you didn't answer my text. I checked my phone. One unread message sent three minutes ago. Mom, I was in class. I couldn't check my phone. She huffed like I was being unreasonable. Well, did you? At this point, the principal was openly staring. Yes, I had a granola bar. My mom sighed with relief. Good. That's all I wanted to know. Click. She hung up. The principal's slowly took her phone back and just stared at me. Your mother called the main office line, had me pull you out of AP biology to ask if you ate breakfast. I nodded, completely mortified. She pressed her lips together, trying not to laugh. Well, at least she cares. I was walking back to class when I got three more texts from my mom. Did you Drink water today. Do you have your jacket? Should I call again to check? I immediately blocked her number for the rest of the school day.

The Uber driver turned around and asked, are you sure you want me to leave you here alone? What do you mean by that? I stared at my Uber driver, Carlos. We just pulled up to my apartment complex after a long day at work. But instead of ending the ride, he was studying my building with genuine concern. Ma'am, I, I'm driving for five years and something's not right here, he said quietly. There's a black sedan that's been following us for the past 20 minutes. Same car, keeping exactly three cars behind us the whole drive. He just pulled into your parking lot right after we did. I turn to look out the back window and my blood ran cold. There was indeed a black car parked under the street light near the entrance with someone still sitting inside watching our vehicle. Carlos continued while keeping his voice low. I first noticed him when we left your office building. I thought it was coincidence. But he followed us through eight different turns, including that detour when I missed the highway exit. Nobody takes that exact route by accident. When I tested him by slowing down, he slowed down. When I sped up, he matched my speed perfectly. My heart started pounding as Carlos pulled, got his phone and showed me photos he'd taken at red lights. The license plate was clearly visible and the driver was definitely focused on our car rather than the road. This is going To sound paranoid, but I think you should call someone before getting out, Carlos said urgently. I've seen this behavior before and people who follow others this systematically aren't planning anything good. The way he's been tracking us suggest he knows your routine and where you live. I tried to think of anyone who might follow me, but I lived quietly with no drama or enemies. Then I remembered recent things that hadn't seemed significant. The feeling of being watched. The same dark car in my mirrors. My neighbor mentioning someone asking about my schedule. Carlos was scrolling through his driver history when his expression changed to confusion. Ma'am, this is strange. I've had three other ride requests to pick you up from your work address in the past two weeks. But when I arrived, you weren't there. Someone kept calling in rides under your name and then no showing. The realization hit me like ice water. Someone had been impersonating me to learn my work schedule and commute patterns. They been calling multiple Uber drivers pretending to be me, asking detailed questions about pickup times and routes home. Carlos continued checking his phone. The other drivers in our group chat mentioned the same thing. Fake ride request from your phone number, always asking about the safest route to your apartment and what time you usually get home from work. Someone's been systematically gathering information about your routine. That's when Carlos noticed something that made him grab my arm. Urgently He's getting out of the car, he whispered. The man from the black sedan was walking directly toward us with determined steps, longer trying to hide his presence. Carlos immediately started the engine and began backing out of the parking space. We need to leave right now, he said, his voice tight with fear. But the man started jogging toward our car and I could see his face clearly now. It was someone I recognized but couldn't immediately place. Carlos floor the gas, racing toward the complex exit while calling 9 1 1 on his hands free system. The man jumped back into his sedan and followed us, this time making no attempt to hide his pursuit. The chase lasted nearly 10 minutes through residential streets with Carlos taking random turns while staying on the line with the 9 1 1 dispatcher who was coordinating with patrol units in the area. The man in the black sedan was driving aggressively, trying to get alongside our car while we sped through neighborhoods. Carlos spotted flashing lights ahead and drove straight toward them, two police cars that had been positioned as a roadblock after the dispatcher's instructions. The black sedan couldn't stop in time and skated into a utility pole. When officers pulled the driver out, I recognized him with six certainty. It was my apartment building's property manager who had access to and information and had been using resident phone numbers to impersonate tenants. Police found detailed files on multiple Female residents, fake ID cards and evidence that he'd been calling ride services while pretending to be different women to learn their schedules and routines. Carlos's instincts had prevented what investigators confirmed was a systematic stalking operation targeting vulnerable female tenants.

My boyfriend ditched me for his discord mods until his roommate said, I'm taking you out. He finally took off his headset. Xavier texted me 30 minutes before our anniversary dinner. Can't make it, babe. The boys need me for raids tonight. I stared at my phone in my brand new dress that cost half my paycheck. This was literally the third time he had stood me up for our anniversary and I had enough. This time I immediately drove to his apartment because I wanted him to see exactly what he was choosing those dumb pixels over. The second I walked through the door, I could hear him screaming at his monitor. Then I heard a voice from the kitchen say, wow, that dress is way too nice for getting stood up. It was Hunter, Xavier's roommate who had moved in six months ago. He was pouring himself a glass of whiskey. Hunter looked showered and dressed like an actual adult. Meanwhile, Xavier was probably still in yesterday's clothes screaming at 12 year olds online. Let me guess the boys needed their tank for tonight's very important digital battle. That definitely couldn't wait, he asked while getting another glass from the cabinet. I laughed bitterly. You know how he is, I said, trying not to cry while Xavier's yelling echoed from his room. Hunter shook his head. Listen, Jules, I've seen him ditch you for regular game nights before, but really on your anniversary? He actually looked angry for Me, which was more emotion than Xavier knew how to show. That's just messed up and you know it. He poured me a glass of wine from a bottle that cost more than Xavier had spent on me in months. We sat there drinking and hunter actually listened when I talked about work. Wait, you got promoted to regional manager? He asked excitedly. Xavier never mentioned that at all. That's huge. I realised my boyfriend didn't even know what my job actually was. But his roommate remembered every detail from our random kitchen conversations. I told Xavier about the promotion two weeks ago, I said. He just said cool and went back to his game. Hunter looked at me sincerely. You deserve someone who throws you a party, not someone who can't look away from a screen. Some, something about the way he looked at me made my heart flutter. Hunter had been there for me more than my actual boyfriend just by answering the door when I showed up. Hey, Xavier, your girlfriend is here in a smoking hot dress, hunter called out during a break in the shooting sounds. But Xavier just yelled back, tell her I'll be done in an hour.

When did you have to flee the country? My wife, Nikki, grabbed my hand so tight I thought she'd break my fingers when the nurse called our names. It was finally our turn to get our first ultrasound and we'd see our baby girl for the first time. I kissed her forehead and told her I loved her and she started crying happy tears. The other couple smiled at us. We were that obvious first time parent couple radiating pure joy. Something was wrong the second we walked up to reception. The receptionist looked at our paperwork way too long, kept flipping pages and frowning. Other nurses were whispering and pointing at us, actually pointing. The receptionist called someone over and they both stared at our forms, whispering frantically. Nikki squeezed my hand. What's happening? I shrugged, trying to stay calm. The ultrasound tech, Roxy, came to get us, but she was acting weird. No smile, no congratulations. She kept asking bizarre questions while spreading gel on Nikki's stomach. Your parents'names again, even though it was right there on the forms. Roxy exchanged a look with the nurse that made my stomach drop. Where were you both born? What hospitals? What year? The questions kept coming. Did we know our blood types? Had either parent been married before? Did we have siblings? Roxy started the ultrasound and everything seemed fine. Baby's heartbeat filled the room at 144 beats per minute. Then Roxy froze. Move the wand back to the same Spot near the shoulder. Her face went pale. She called Doctor Braxton in immediately. Doctor Braxton looked at the screen and kept counting something, moving the wand to the shoulder area, repeatedly taking screenshots, more screenshots. Is our baby okay? Nikki asked through tears. Please just tell, tell us what's wrong. He cleared his throat. Vital signs are strong. Heart rate perfect. Growth on track. But he kept returning to that shoulder area, whispering to Roxy, who was typing frantically. They kept looking at our paperwork, then the screen, then us, like solving a terrible puzzle. After 20 minutes, a nurse pulled us into a private consultation room. Her hands were shaking as she opened our files. She pointed at things we'd never noticed. Same rare blood type, AB negative. Have you guys ever been blood tested? Now that I thought about it, I don't think I've ever gotten any testing done. However, I knew something was still off. The nurse says probably nothing, but good to know your genetic history for the baby's medical records. Nikki was so worried, we got the blood test. That same day, the lab tech did the same double take everyone had been doing. Nikki's parents showed up, too, to comfort her. And as we were waiting for her to open the email, we stood behind her. She read for maybe 10 seconds, then the phone just fell out of her hands. The scream that came out of her wasn't human. She collapsed onto The floor, sobbing so hard she was choking, couldn't breathe, couldn't speak. Just kept shaking her head, no, My mom went white as a sheet. Nicki's mom started crying before she even knew what the results said. Our dad's just stood there frozen. I tried to grab the phone to see what was wrong, but Nicki pulled it against her chest screaming, we can't be. We can't be. This isn't real. What? What is it? I yelled. We're, this says we're siblings. Nicki finally gasped out. Everyone looked at each other. Then the room exploded. What her dad said? But we all heard her. My mom literally ran to the bathroom and threw up. They all started yelling, demanding we divorce. Nikki's mom said, we destroyed both families. Everyone would know the shame would kill them. Nikki grabbed my hand and we just ran out the door into our car. Our parents screaming behind us. We didn't stop. Our daughter was born with three arms, but now nobody can judge us because we since moved to Alabama.

For months, I've been having these crazy stomach cramps that made me double over in the middle of class. My parents kept saying it was just stress from school, maybe too much coffee or whatever, but our family doctor wasn't buying it and sent me to get a full allergy panel done. I remember sitting in that sterile clinic room, rolling my eyes as the nurse prepped, like, 50 different allergen samples. I was thinking, great, I'm probably allergic to peanuts or milk like every other kid. Maybe shellfish if I'm unlucky. The nurse started pricking my arm with tiny needles, each one containing a different substance. Dust, mites, pollen, cat dander, the usual suspects. She kept checking her watch and marking down reactions as little red bumps appeared on my skin. Most were barely visible, just tiny dots that looked like mosquito bites. But then I noticed her face change when she looked at one specific spot on my arm. The area around this one test site was literally bubbling up like a balloon. My skin was bright red and swelling so fast, I could actually watch it grow. The nurse called in Doctor Kim. The allergist took one look at my arm, and I swear her clipboard hit the floor. She whispered, oh, no, Under her breath. And immediately started ordering additional tests. I was like, what the hell is happening? What could possibly be that bad? Turns out I was severe.

And after I got caught fainting at school, my punishment was watching the family eat pizza while I had ice water. Dad texted that he was coming home early, and mom scrambled to make me a plate that looked normal from a distance. He walked in. He relaxed. Good. Everyone's eating. That was when I stopped fighting. I looked in the mirror one morning and didn't see the skeleton everyone else saw. I saw what mom had been telling me for years. Too much space, too much flesh, too much everything. You're right. I told her at breakfast. I'm disgusting. I don't deserve

Our school started charging $50 per semester for lockers because they claimed they needed money for maintenance and security upgrades. Most kids just complained, but paid up anyway. My friend Marcus was different for, though. He actually started paying attention to where that money was going. It started when Marcus timed how long it took maintenance to fix anything around school. Broken water fountain by the cafeteria. Three weeks in, counting. Flickering fluorescent lights in the gym that gave everyone headaches. Two months later, still strobing like a disco. The bathroom door in the science wing that wouldn't lock properly. They just put up an out of order sign and called it solved. But somehow, magically, they had money for 12 brand new high definition security cameras pointed directly at the lockers. Not the parking lot where kids cars actually got broken into, not the entrance where fights happened. Just the lockers that we were now paying 50 bucks to use. Marcus got suspicious and started doing what Marcus does best. Digging. During study hall, instead of pretending to read his chemistry textbook, he was on the school computers pulling up public records and budget reports. That's when he found it. The security company that installed those cameras. Owned by one Richard Thompson. Our principal's last name. Thompson. A little more digging revealed that Richard Thompson was Principal Thompson's brother in law. The whole locker fee scam was basically funding their family business. While our ceiling tiles literally had water Stains from leaks they claimed they couldn't afford to fix. But here's where Marcus proved he's not just smart. He's strategically brilliant. He discovered that according to state Education Code Section 4 8 9 0 4, charging students for basic educational storage violates equal access laws. School was literally breaking state law by making lockers cost money. Instead of marching straight to the principal's office like some naive freshman, Marcus had a better plan. He spent his weekend printing out copies of the relevant legal codes, complete with highlighted sections and easy to understand summaries. Then he started his gorilla inform

My husband filed for divorce after my father died, thinking he was entitled to half of the inheritance left to me. But he didn't count on one thing. Dad and I had our complicated history. He'd been absent through most of my childhood, chasing business deals across three states while mom raised me alone. When he finally showed up for my wedding, he'd missed every school play, every birthday, every moment that mattered. But in those final months after his heart attack, something shifted between us. Trevor thought he'd hit the Jackpot. When the lawyer read Dad's will, $2 million, the Lakehouse and a portfolio of investments all left to me, I watched Trevor's eyes light up as he calculated his half community property. He kept saying, what's yours is mine. The divorce papers arrived two weeks after the funeral. Attached was a letter from his attorney demanding immediate disclosure of all inherited assets. Trevor had already moved in with his secretary, but apparently he planned to fund their new life with my father's money. What Trevor didn't know was that dad and I had spent those last months talking, really talking the first time in decades. He told me about the mistakes he'd made, the choices that kept him away. But mostly we talked about Trevor. Dad saw things I've been too blind to notice, how Trevor dismissed my opinions at dinner parties, how he'd roll his eyes when I mentioned going back to school, how he'd started working late. More often, coming home smelling like unfamiliar perfume. Three months before he died, dad called me to his office. He pulled out a thick folder and placed it on his mahogany desk. Inside were photos, Trevor entering a downtown hotel with his secretary, credit card statement showing expensive dinners I'd never attended, hotel receipts spanning back two years. Private investigators report documenting every affair, every lie, every moment of betrayal. Dad's final gift wasn't just the inheritance. It was Protection. The prenup Trevor had insisted on before our wedding, the one that protected his assets but left me with almost nothing.

What's the funniest thing you've ever done just to prove a point? Back in college, my roommate Zach was one of those guys who always thought he was right, even if it meant arguing that water isn't actually wet. One night we got into this completely pointless debate about whether goldfish had memories longer than 3 seconds. Zack was stubborn, saying their memory was short. It's scientifically proven, he said. They're like little swimming potatoes. I wasn't buying it. I remembered reading somewhere that goldfish could actually learn tricks. Zack just rolled his eyes and said, yeah, then prove it. Challenge accepted. The next day, I went out and bought a small fish tank, some decorations and a goldfish. I named him Newton because clearly this fish was about to graduate college before Zack did. I binged YouTube to tutorials on fish training and started teaching Newton to swim through a little hoop and tap a red dot on a stick in exchange for food. The first few days were rough, but after a week of consistent training, Newton was getting the hang of it. By Week 2, he could do the tricks without hesitation. Finally, I called Zach over, smiling like a mad scientist. Alright, genius. Watch this. He stood there, arms folded, ready to laugh. I dropped the hoop in and Newton swam right through it like a pro. Zack raised an eyebrow, still unconvinced. Then I held up the red dot and Newton swam straight over and Tapped it like he'd done it a thousand times. Zack's mouth fell open. No shot. That's gotta be a fluke. I kept going, having Newton do it again and again, same result every time. Zack just stood there and didn't say a word for the rest of the day. A few days later, I caught him googling, can goldfish be trained? He never admitted I was right, but his sir.

The Amazon driver asked me, you live alone here, right, ma'am? No, my boyfriend just went out for orange juice, I lied, immediately regretting opening the door this wide. The guy clutched my package in his hands and kept looking past me into my apartment. No boyfriend here, I think he said in a thick Indian accent that made my skin crawl. Maybe are you living with family, parents? I reached for my package wanting to end this conversation any second, but he pulled it back. My boyfriend will be back any minute now, I said louder, hoping this creepy dude would get the hint. The driver shook his head slowly muttering something I couldn't understand. His eyes kept scanning my living room like he was memorizing it. I panicked, thinking he was about to lunch slam the door in his face and turned the deadbolt. Look, I've seen enough tik toks about creepy delivery guys to know where this goes. But fifteen minutes later, when I peeked through my blinds to check if he was gone, his white van was still there. When our eyes met through the window, I dropped to the floor and once again waited for him to leave. But then my phone lit up with a text from him saying, please come outside. Need to talk. Important thing. I didn't reply, so he sent another text. Get in delivery van. I show you something. I felt goosebumps all over my skin from how sketchy this Guy was. And I almost wanted to call the cops. But then he texted again saying, you're not safe there alone. Please trust. Very urgent matter. I took a deep breath and texted him back tell, telling him to leave immediately. I even threatened that if he didn't take his truck off my property, I would call the cops. But as I was typing, I suddenly heard footsteps in my bedroom. The thing is, I actually was home alone, so these footsteps could only belong to one person. I rushed to the kitchen, grabbed a knife and slowly crept towards my bedroom as I opened the door.

Why did the divorce lawyer charge us $500 to watch me dance like a robot? My wife Elisa accused me of having an affair based on my fitness tracker data. But when she made me show the divorce lawyer the actual footage, he teared up and had to leave the room. Three months ago, Elisa decided we should sync our fitness trackers to keep each other motivated. Great idea, right? Wrong. Monday afternoon, she texted me 20 question marks. Just question marks. When I got home, she was sitting at the kitchen table with her laptop open. My fitness data pulled up on the screen. Interesting workout you had today, she said. Voice deadly calm. Heart rate of 180 beats per minute for 90 minutes at 2 p m. At an address that's definitely not your office. I felt the blood drain from my face. I can explain. Oh, I'm sure you can. She spun the laptop around. Every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, same location, same time, same intensity. I opened my mouth to tell her about the classes, but my phone buzzed. The preview showed R. Don't forget your hips tomorrow. And bring water. You sweat like a fountain. Elisa's face went from suspicious to murderous. Your hips! Your hips! It's not what you think. Whose R? And why does she have a dancing emoji? She was already pulling up our credit card statement. Studio Rosa Private Sessions. $1,200. Private sessions with Rosa. Rosa is 70 years. I don't Care how old your mistress is. That's when things spiraled completely out of control. Elisa's sister turned into Sherlock Holmes overnight finding studio Rosa's website, which unhelpfully just said, private instruction by appointment only. No photos, no details, just an address and that cryptic message her sister also discovered. I've been telling my boss I had physical therapy appointments every Monday, Wednesday and Friday afternoon. Physical therapy? Alyssa's BAT, three times a week? Is that what they're calling it now?

What's the most ridiculous school rule that students destroyed with loopholes? My school had this completely insane bathroom rule where you could only use the restroom twice per day. Two times. That was it. They gave each teacher a clipboard with our names on it, and they had to check us off every single time we asked to go. The whole thing started because some kids were apparently vaping in the bathrooms. So instead of dealing with those specific kids, the administration decided to punish everyone. They hired Mrs. Wilson as the bathroom monitor, and she took her job way too seriously. This woman would literally stand outside the bathrooms, timing how long we were in there. By November, half the school was walking around looking like they were about to explode. My friend Connor actually wet himself during third period math because he already used his two bathroom passes for the day. The teacher just ignored him and kept teaching while this poor kid sat there humiliated. That's when Emma had enough. She was this quiet girl who never caused trouble, but she was also the smartest kid in our grade. During lunch, she pulled out the student handbook and started reading through all the bathroom policies. He found something interesting on page 47. The rules said students were limited to two bathroom visits per day, but it didn't say anything about how long each visit could be. Emma realized we could technically stay in there for hours as Long as we only went twice, Emma started spreading the word. She told us to bring books, Max, whatever we needed. The plan was simple. Make each bathroom visit count. So we did exactly that. The next Monday, I grabbed a sandwich and my history textbook before asking for my first bathroom pass. I stayed in there for 45 minutes studying for my quiz next period. When I came back, my teacher looked annoyed.

What did your kids teacher do that made you snap? My 14 year old daughter with intellectual disabilities looked up at me with ink blackened hands and said, I'm a good helper instead of telling me what she Learned that day. Kayla had always loved showing me her worksheets after school. Her teacher, Missus Gracie, practically shoved me out the door when I tried to ask questions. I peered back through the window and saw something that made my blood run cold. Kayla was completely alone, feeding papers into an industrial shredder while every other kid was at lunch eating together. Started dropping by unannounced and each visit revealed something worse. The first day Kayla was organizing supplies. The next visit she was scrubbing toilets without gloves. By Wednesday, I found her using chemical cleaners that required ventilation masks. She didn't have one. Her hands were cracked and bleeding. Thursday she couldn't hold a pencil because her fingers were so cut up from sorting metal recycling. I dumped her backpack that night and found nothing. Not a single worksheet in three months. When I tested her, she couldn't write her own name anymore. She used to know the alphabet. Confronted Missus Gracie who smiled and said Kayla was getting life skills. When I demanded to see homework, she said these special helpers don't need that and walked away. I called other families and discovered something horrifying. Eight kids were doing custodial work full time. One boy had chemical burns. Another Girl had been cleaning cafeteria grease traps. I installed a tracking app on Kayla's phone and watched for a week, four hours daily in the maintenance building, two hours in the main office, never in any classroom. When I asked Kayla when she last read a book, she couldn't remember. She said missus Gracie told her she was too special for regular classes but perfect for important helper work. The principal insisted everything was legal. When I complained, he refused to show me any documentation. Other teachers started avoiding me in the hallways. Then Kayla came home with a bandaged hand from the paper shredder she'd been told not to tell me. That's when I knew this went deeper than just one teacher. Principal was protecting missus Gracie. The other teachers knew. Everyone knew these kids were being used and nobody cared enough to stop it. My daughter was disappearing into their free labor system, forgetting everything she once knew. And they were calling it education. I demanded an emergency meeting and showed them Kayla's tracking data. The special education director barely glanced at it before saying this was vocational training. Prepare.

Girlfriend said I share too much about my feelings, so I stopped sharing anything at all. Jess came over to my place Friday night and I could tell something was bothering her by the way she kept sighing. You know what Britney told me today? She said flopping down on my couch. Her boyfriend is so mysterious and she's obsessed with him. Meanwhile, you texted me 12 times about being nervous for your presentation. The way she said it made me feel like I was some kind of burden. I wish you were more mysterious, more of a challenge. I should have known this would end badly when three weeks later she'd be crying at my door. But that night I just felt hurt and said, fine, I'll be mysterious that night. I usually would have texted her good night, but I didn't and it felt wrong not doing it. She sent me three question marks right away and I just wrote back all good and left it at that. Saturday morning came and normally I text her about my coffee and ask what she was up to, but I kept my phone in my pocket. By noon she was texting you okay and I just sent a thumbs up, which killed me because I actually wanted to talk to her. Monday was the worst because I got the promotion I've been working for and all I wanted was to call her and celebrate. When we went to dinner that Night she asked about my day and I just said same old while scrolling through my phone, even though inside I was bursting to tell her. She leaned across the table trying to figure out what was going on with me. You seem different, she said. Good, different. And the crazy part was she seemed more into me than she had in months, which made me feel powerful but also completely hollow inside. The second week she started showing up at my place without calling first and cooking these fancy dinners, basically doing anything to crack me open. I can't figure you out anymore, she said. Wednesday night and she sounded excited about it. Britney so jealous. She as I got the mysterious boyfriend Jackpot. I wanted to tell her how dumb this whole thing was and how much I missed just talking to her normally, but I just shrugged and kept watching TV. my dad called because my mom was in the hospital for minor surgery and he was freaking out. I spent three hours calming him down while Jess sat next to me trying to figure out what was happening. After I hung up, she asked, is everything okay? And I wanted to fall into her arms and tell her everything, family, stuff. I said instead, it's handled. She me harder than she had in months and whispered, you're so strong. But I wasn't strong at all. I was just pretending. The third, Thursday night at eleven, PM Jess showed up at my door with her makeup running down her face, shaking.

My boyfriend ditched me for his discord mods until his roommate said I'm taking you out. He finally took off his headset. Xavier texted me 30 minutes before our anniversary dinner. Can't make it, babe, the boys need me for raids tonight. I stared at my phone in my brand new dress that cost half my paycheck. This was literally the third time he had stood me up for our anniversary, and I had enough this time. I immediately drove to his apartment because I wanted him to see exact, exactly what he was choosing those dumb pixels over. The second I walked through the door, I could hear him screaming at his monitor. Then I heard a voice from the kitchen say, wow, that dress is way too nice for getting stood up. It was Hunter, Xavier's roommate who had moved in six months ago. He was pouring himself a glass of whiskey. Hunter looked showered and dressed like an actual adult. Meanwhile, Xavier was probably still in yesterday's clothes, aiming at 12 year olds online. Let me guess, the boys needed their tank for tonight's very important digital battle that definitely couldn't wait? He asked while getting another glass from the cabinet. I laughed bitterly. You know how he is, I said, trying not to cry while Xavier's yelling echoed from his room. Hunter shook his head. Listen, Jules, I've seen him ditch you for regular game nights before, but really, on your anniversary? He actually looked angry. For me, which was more emotion than Xavier knew how to show. That's just messed up, and you know it. He poured me a glass of wine from a bottle that cost more than Xavier had spent on me in months. Sat there drinking, and hunter actually listened when I talked about work. Wait, you got promoted to regional manager? He asked excitedly. Xavier never mentioned that at all. That's huge! I realized. My boyfriend didn't even know what my job actually was, but his roommate remembered every detail from our random kitchen conversations. I told Xavier about the promotion two weeks ago, I said. He just said, cool and went back to his game. Hunter looked at me sincerely. You deserve someone who throws you a party, not someone who can't look away from a screen. Something about the way he looked at me made my heart flutter. Hunter had been there for me more than my actual boyfriend, just by answering the door when I showed up. Hey, Xavier, your girlfriend is here in a smoking hot dress! Hunter called out during a break in the shooting sounds, but Xavier just yelled back, tell her I'll be done in an hour. Hunter's face went dark, and he grabbed his car keys off the counter. You. You know what? Forget waiting around for him. I'm taking you to that anniversary dinner myself, he announced, loud enough for Xavier to hear over his game. The gaming sounds cut off completely. And Xavier's door flew open so hard it hit the wall. What did you just say? Xavier demanded, while still wearing his stupid game

What happened when your fiance wanted a hall pass? My fiance, Lauren brought this up at the bridal shop during her final dress fitting. We should have last hurrah, she said. One month to date other people before we get married. I was confused why. I want to experience someone else and have fun before we get tied down forever. She kept looking excited about something. She'd been talking about her trainer, Derek, every single day for weeks, always mentioning how funny he was, how he understood her. Just one month, I asked. Yes, then we get married and never date anyone else. I realized she just wanted permission to date Derek. Okay, I said. She was so happy. Really? Thank you. You're amazing. That night she went on a date with Derek. I sat home alone for three days. I stayed home while she went out with him every night. She never asked if I was okay. She never noticed I wasn't eating. Then I had an idea. I would call Madison, her worst enemy. For a week, I watched Lauren leave for dates with Derek. She'd post pictures everywhere, beach trips, dinners, gym selfies. She wanted everyone to see. One night she came home talking about their plans. Derek found us this perfect apartment near his gym. She said, us, I asked for after she caught herself. I mean, if things were different. But I heard what she really meant. That's when I called Madison. She used to Be Lauren's best friend until six months ago. Madison got promoted instead of Lauren. Lauren told their whole office that Madison was sleeping with their boss. It wasn't true, but it ruined Madison's reputation. Lauren's having a hall pass with her trainer. I told Madison for a month before our wedding. Madison was quiet. Then she laughed. Let me guess. She planning more than a month? I think so. Wanna get coffee tomorrow? Madison asked. She humiliated me at work. Maybe it's time. She knows how it feels. I posted our coffee picture the next day. Lauren saw it. Within minutes. Madison, she screamed when she called. You're with Derek, I said, not her. Anyone but her. You said one person for a month. This is mine. She hung up. For the next two weeks, I kept seeing Madison. Lauren got more frantic each time her family mentioned seeing us together. Her sister saw us at lunch. Her cousin saw us at the movies. Stop embarrassing me, Lauren would yell. You started this, I'd remind her. Three days before the rehearsal dinner, Lauren came home crying. Please end it with Madison. Are you ending it with Derek? The rehearsal dinner is family only. Don't bring her then don't bring him, I said. She looked away. He's already invited. The night of the rehearsal dinner, Lauren walked in with Derek on her arm.

When I was 10, my parents read my diary and punished me for what I wrote. I had a small purple diary with a limsy lock. To me, it was sacred, a place where I could say what I couldn't out loud. I filled it with doodles, secrets about crushes and thoughts I didn't trust anyone else with. One evening, I came downstairs and froze. My diary was on the kitchen table, wide open. My parents sat there waiting. My mom's voice was sharp. So this is what you think of us? My dad looked disappointed. On the page, my mom had circled a line, sometimes I feel like they only love me when I'm perfect. My chest tightened. I wanted to explain, but the words stuck. Instead of asking me why I felt that way, they scolded me. They called me disrespectful and ungrateful. Then they punished me. No TV, no playing outside, more chores. That night, I curled up in my room, clutching the diary like it was both the weapon and the wound. It wasn't the punishment that hurt most. It was knowing my private thoughts weren't safe anymore. The one place I trusted had been stolen. For weeks, I stopped writing. Every time I picked up a pen, I felt their eyes on the page. I Learned to swallow my feelings, to keep them locked inside instead of on paper. Years later, I started journaling again, hiding notebooks in places no one could find even now. As an adult, I hesitate before writing certain things as if that night still lingers in the back of my mind. My parents thought they were teaching me respect. What I really Learned was that my feelings weren't welcome in their house. And sometimes when I write today, I still picture that 10 year old girl wishing someone had asked her why she felt unloved.

When were you glad someone tried to kill you? I never expected Megan to approach me that day in chemistry class, let alone start flirting while we worked on our lab assignment together. She was laughing at my terrible jokes about chemical bonds, playfully hitting my arm and even wrote her number on my notebook with a little heart next to it. The whole thing felt surreal until I noticed her ex boyfriend, Josh, glaring at us from across the room with this murderous intensity that made my stomach drop. When Megan leaned in close to whisper something about our next study session, I saw Josh's jaw clench so hard I thought he might crack a tooth. After class, he shoulder checked me hard enough to send my books, then stood over me while I picked them up, not saying a word, but making his message crystal clear. Megan apologized later, explaining they'd only broken up two weeks ago and Josh was having trouble accepting it was over. But she promised he was all bark and no bite. That assessment proved tragically wrong when I found my locker covered in crude drawings and threats the next morning with stay away from her scratched into the metal so deep it could can be painted over. The harassment escalated quickly from intimidation to outright stalking with Josh following me between classes, sitting directly behind me in the cafeteria while breathing heavily on my neck and accidentally spilling his drink on my backpack. Twice in one week. That night I woke up to my mom screaming because someone had spray painted you're chopped across our garage door in blood red letters that drip like something from a horror movie. The next morning we discovered my car had been key so badly that entire panels would need replacing. My parents wanted to call the police, but I had no proof it was Josh. And I knew that without evidence, he'd just deny everything and make my life even worse. The psychological torture was working because I started avoiding Megan, terrified of what Josh might do next. But he kept texting me saying she missed talking to me and hated that her psycho ex was ruining something good. I knew I couldn't let this continue destroying my life, my property and my family's sense of security. Then I got lucky. I forgot my textbook and doubled back to my.

The bullies thought I was still their scrawny punching bag. Wait until they see what a year in China taught me. I start seventh grade with a renewed boost of confidence after spending a year with my grandparents in China. Walking into the school, I spot my worst nightmare. I knew this moment would come eventually. There's Shane, still the same 5 feet 8 inches tower of teenage cruelty, flanked by his usual suspects, Minion 1 and Minion 2. Such loyal followers. I'm still only 5 feet 2 inches and probably look exactly the same to them. Same messy brown hair, same hand me down clothes, same kid they used to stuff into lockers every Tuesday. Like clockwork. Well, well, well, look who's back, Shane announces loud enough for half the hallway to hear. We missed our little toilet bowl cleaner. Minion one actually claps his hands together like he's genuinely excited. Dude, remember when we made him eat that sandwich off the bathroom floor? They're laughing about it like it's their fondest memory. And I feel that familiar burning in my chest. But this time it feels different. Controlled. My grandfather's voice echoes in my head. Anger is fire. You can let it burn you, or you can forge steel with it. Minion two steps closer, invading my personal space. Hope you didn't get too comfortable wherever you went, because nothing's changed here. He shoves my shoulder, testing to see if I'll react the same way I used to. Cowering and apologizing instead, I steady myself and look him directly in the eye. Everything's changed, I say quietly, but Minion 2 just laughs and walks away with his friends. Same scared little mouse. Shane calls over his shoulder. See you in P E. Bathroom, boy. P E. Class arrives like a death sentence, and of course coach pairs us up for defensive exercises, which basically his excuse to let kids beat each other up legally. Shane immediately volunteers to be my partner, grinning like Christmas morning. This is going to be fun! He tells Minion 1 and Minion 2, who are partnered nearby. I've been saving up a year's worth of frustration. He starts small an accidental elbow to my ribs during warm UPS. Oops! Sorry Mouse Boy, didn't mean to hurt you. When I tell him I'm not weak anymore, he literally doubles over laughing. Not weak? You're the same 70 pound scarecrow who cried when I gave you a wedgie! That's when he crosses the line. My husband hit me in front of his mother, but her reaction shocked everyone in the room. For three years, I've been walking on eggshells around David. The slap started small, a quick backhand when dinner was cold, a shove when I disagreed with him, always behind closed doors, always followed by apologies and promises it would never happen again. His mother had been visiting for the weekend, and I'd been trying so hard to be the perfect wife. Margaret Morrison was everything I wasn't, polished, educated, from old money. She made it clear from the beginning that I wasn't good enough for her son. The girl from the wrong side of town who trapped her precious boy with an unplanned pregnancy that we lost three months into our marriage, made her favourite meals, cleaned the house twice and bit my tongue when she criticized everything from my cooking to my outfit choices. She had this way of looking at me like I was a stain on her expensive furniture. The explosion came over something stupid. I'd accidentally used the good China for lunch instead of saving it for dinner. It was an honest mistake. I've been so nervous about impressing her that I grabbed the wrong plates from the cabinet. David's face went red the moment he saw the delicate porcelain. What the hell is wrong with you, he said, his voice low and dangerous. I specifically told you those were for tonight when the Hendersons come over. I'm Sorry, I whispered, already reaching to clear the table with shaking hands. I'll wash them carefully and reset everything with the everyday dishes. His mother was sitting right there sipping her tea like nothing was happening. I thought maybe her presence would keep him calm. I'd never been more wrong about anything in my life. David grabbed my wrist so hard, I felt the bones grind together. You never listen, do you? You're too stupid to follow simple instructions. How many times do I have to explain things before they penetrate that thick skull of yours? I tried to pull away, but his grip tightened until tears sprang to my eyes. Please, I said quietly, glancing nervously at his mother. You're hurting me. His mother continued drinking her tea, her face completely expressionless. No help was coming from that direction. That's when he did it, right in front of his mother, right in the middle of their pristine dining room with its crystal chandelier and mahogany table. He drew back his hand and slapped me across the face so hard my ears rang and I tasted blood. I stood there stunned, my cheek burning like fire, waiting for his mother to gasp or object or do something, anything. She'd always been so proper, so concerned with appearances and social etiquette. Instead, she set down her teacup with a delicate clink and looked directly at her son. The sound seemed to echo in the sudden silence. David Anthony Morrison, she said. Her voice cutting through the silence like a blade. What did you just do? Something in her.
