What's the best meal you've ever eaten? My mom once made spaghetti that was so bad it got me grounded for a month. Growing up, my mom was obsessed with proving she was a better cook than my stepdad's ex wife. She'd spend hours watching cooking shows, buying fancy ingredients and forcing us to try her experimental dishes. The problem, she was absolutely terrible at cooking, like accidentally set cereal on fire. Terrible. But we weren't allowed to say anything negative about her food. One time, my brother gagged on her special meatloaf and had to write Mom's cooking is a blessing 500 times. When. When I was 14, she decided to enter a local cooking competition. The grand prize was a feature in our town's newspaper. She spent weeks practicing her signature dish, seafood spaghetti with a secret sauce. The sauce was bright orange and smelled like someone had mixed ketchup with fish food. The night before the competition, she made us be her test audience. As soon as she put the plate in front of me, I knew something was wrong. The pasta was this weird gray color and there were whole chunks of garlic floating in the sauce. Not minced garlic, entire cloves. My stepdad took one bite and his face turned green, but he forced a smile and said, unique flavor profile, honey. My little sister started crying when mom tried to make her eat a shrimp that was still partially frozen when it was my Turn. I couldn't do it. I couldn't lie anymore. I took one bite and immediately spit it out into my napkin. Mom, this is inedible. Pasta is raw in the middle. The sauce tastes like battery acid. And I think this shrimp might be alive. The kitchen went silent. My stepdad's fork clattered onto his plate. My sister stopped crying and stared at me with huge eyes. Mom's face turned the same color as her horrible sauce. Instead of yelling, she got scary calm. Oh, you think you could do better? She pushed her chair back from the table. The kitchen's all yours, Gordon Ramsay. I should have backed down. Instead, I stood up and said, actually, yes, I've been secretly taking cooking classes at the community center for the past year because I was tired of eating food that tastes like punishment. Mom's eyes started twitching. Prove it. I went to the kitchen and pulled out everything I needed. I've been practicing my own pasta sauce recipe for months, tweaking at each time. While I cooked, mom stood in the corner with her arms crossed making these little hmm noises. The thing is, I actually knew what I would.

I saw a man proudly admitting to arson in court, and he was so badass about it that he walked free. I was on jury duty. And the man being prosecuted was charged with burning down a farm building. Just a week before the building had burned down, the man was seen methodically moving all the valuables out of the barn. He was also seen meticulously mowing the hayfields for a 50 yards radius all around the barn to ensure the fire wouldn't spread. The day he set fire to the barn, he was seen walking around the entire thing, pouring something from a blue gas can onto the bottom of the barn walls. Not even a minute later, the entire building was fully engulfed in flames. The witness, who was the man's neighbor and had seen this entire thing, called the fire department and reported that the man had set the barn on fire. Fire department was on scene in about five minutes, but by that time the barn was already beyond saving. They did smell diesel fuel, though, and a quick investigation said it was clear arson. They arrested the man on the spot, but he refused to say anything. He also refused to talk to the DA and immediately asked for his lawyer. While on trial, the prosecution stated that they will prove the man, who was a farmer, set his own barn on fire. The barn was insured, meaning insurance fraud was the motive. They called All the expected witnesses, the neighbor, the fireman who smelled fuel, they played the 911 call, and so on. The defense lawyer did absolutely nothing this entire time. After about 40 minutes, the prosecution was finally done, and they had proved beyond doubt that the man set his own barn on fire for insurance fraud. Or so they thought. It was now the defense's turn. The man's lawyer called the man up on the stand. His first question to the farmer being prosecuted was, let's cut to the chase. Did you burn your barn down? Yep. The man responded, why did you do it? It was old and rotten with termites. It was going to fall down. Not safe to be kept standing. The man replied, hmm. Have you always burned down old farm buildings? The lawyer asked, yep. I'm a farmer, and my daddy was a farmer, and he did the same thing before me. The lawyer then asked, are you aware that you need a permit to burn debris in this county? The man replied, my family been doing it like that on this farm. We never had no permit. My farm is located in an active agriculture zone and is exempt from needing a permit to burn down debris. It was at this moment I turned to look at the prosecution's face, and their lawyer was damn near going pale. This was already enough to get the man off the hook, but he wasn't done. His lawyer Continued if all of that is true

Parents with adopted kids. Why did you choose adoption? When my husband and I first walked into the foster care center, we weren't planning on adopting three kids at once. But that's exactly what happened after we met Noah. Noah was 12, sitting alone in the corner of the playroom, teaching himself sign language from a worn out library book. The social worker explained that Noah had two younger sisters, penny and Grace, ages 6 and 4. Their previous foster family had separated them, and Noah hadn't seen his sisters in months. That night, I couldn't sleep. I kept thinking about how Noah was teaching himself sign language just so he could communicate with Grace, who was born deaf. The social worker mentioned that in their previous foster home, Grace had no one who could sign with her except Noah. We decided to take all three kids for a weekend visit. Noah was suspicious at first, watching our every move like a hawk. He'd portion out the food we gave his sisters, saving half of each meal just in case. Bedtime. We found him sleeping on the floor between his sister's beds. The real turning point came during breakfast. Grace accidentally knocked over her orange juice, and she immediately started crying, signing sorry over and over. No! Noah jumped between her and my husband, arms spread wide, expecting punishment. Instead, my husband got down on his knees, used the basic sign language we've been learning, and told Grace, accidents happen. Let's clean this together. The look on Noah's face, I'll never forget it. Pure shock. That weekend turned into a week, then a month. We enrolled in sign language classes as a family. Noah started teaching us the signs he'd made up with Grace. Their own secret language. Penny, the middle child, began sleeping through the night instead of having nightmares. But just as things were settling, their birth mother resurfaced, demanding visitation rights. Noah became withdrawn again, hoarding food in his room. Grace stopped signing altogether. Penny's nightmares returned. The birth mother missed the first two scheduled visits. On the third try, she showed up high. Noah took one look at her and signed to Grace, cover your eyes. That's when I knew these were our kids. We were going to fight for them. The legal battle lasted eight months. We discovered she'd been arrested twice since abandoning them. Every time she missed a court date, Noah would ask if we were sending them back. We kept promising we weren't going anywhere. The day we won full custody, we celebrated by letting the kids pick dinner. They chose breakfast food. Noah made chocolate chip pancakes, his specialty. Grace taught us the sign for Forever Family. Penny drew a picture of all of us. We thought that was our happy ending. But then Noah dropped a bomb. He asked if he could change his last name to ours. When we said yes, Grace and penny wanted to change theirs, too. The next surprise came from Noah. He'd been saving his allowance for months. He bought us each a sign language dictionary with a note that read, thanks for learning my language. Now I want to learn yours. Last week, Grace had a dance recital. Noah signed every word of the music for her while she performed. Penny filmed it all. My husband cried, though he denies it. This morning, I found Noah teaching the girls how to make pancakes. They had flour everywhere. Three years ago, that would have sent them into a panic, expecting punishment. Today, they were

What's the best meal you've ever eaten? My mom once made spaghetti that was so bad, it got me grounded for a month. Growing up, my mom was obsessed with proving she was a better cook than my stepdad's ex wife. She'd spend hours watching cooking shows, buying fancy ingredients, and forcing us to try her experimental dishes. The problem? She was absolutely terrible at cooking. Like, accidentally set cereal on fire terrible. But we weren't allowed to say anything negative about her food. One time, my brother gagged on her special meatloaf and had to write Mom's cooking is a blessing 500 times. When. When I was 14, she decided to enter a local cooking competition. The grand prize was a feature in our town's newspaper. She spent weeks practicing her signature dish, seafood spaghetti with a secret sauce. The sauce was bright orange and smelled like someone had mixed ketchup with fish food. The night before the competition, she made us be her test audience. As soon as she put the plate in front of me, I knew something was wrong. The pasta was this weird gray color, and there were whole chunks of garlic floating in the sauce. Not minced garlic, entire cloves. My stepdad took one bite, and his face turned green. But he forced a smile and said, unique flavor profile, honey. My little sister started crying when mom tried to make her eat a shrimp that was still partially frozen. When it was my Turn! I couldn't do it. I couldn't lie anymore. I took one bite and immediately spit it out into my napkin. Mom, this is inedible. The pasta is raw in the middle, the sauce tastes like battery acid, and I think this shrimp might be alive. The kitchen went silent. My stepdad's fork clattered onto his plate. My sister stopped crying and stared at me with huge eyes. Mom's face turned the same color as her horrible sauce. Instead of yelling, she got scary calm. Oh, you think you could do better? She pushed her chair back from the table. The kitchen's all yours, Gordon Ramsay. I should have backed down. Instead, I stood up and said, actually, yes. I've been secretly taking cooking classes at the community center for the past year because I was tired of eating food that tastes like punishment. Mom's eyes started twitching. Prove it. I went to the kitchen and pulled out everything I needed.

My daughter texted, Dad, Mom's been bringing men over while you're deployed. I replied, thank you for your honesty, sweetheart. Then I made sure her mother's secret wasn't secret anymore. Charlotte's text hit me at 3:00am. Overseas, my 16 year old was always direct, but this felt different. Dad, Mom has been having book club every Wednesday, but there's only one guy who comes over. They drink wine, and he doesn't leave until morning. My wife Christina taught high school English. Book club sounded plausible, except we've been married 12 years, and she'd never mentioned loving books. Charlotte, are you sure about this? Dad, I'm not stupid. His car is here every week. Same blue Honda. Yesterday, I saw his coffee mug in the sink with lipstick on it. Mom doesn't wear lipstick to book club. Smart kid. Takes after me. Last Wednesday, I came downstairs for water around 11 p m. They were on the couch watching some romantic movie. When mom saw me, she jumped up and said, Mister Huang was just leaving, but his car was still there at 7 a m. Mister Huang. That narrowed it down. Significant. Charlotte, keep acting normal. Don't let mom know. We talked about this already. Been doing it for three weeks. Dad, I'm not about to blow it now. Instead of confronting Christina direct, I called my neighbor Bruce, retired Marine, who walks his dog past our house twice daily. can you snap a photo of that blue Honda's License plate next time. Already got it, buddy. Been wondering when you'd ask. And fishy to me. Quick license plate search through military contacts revealed the car belonged to Steven Huang, another teacher at Christina's school. Married with two kids. I found Steven's Facebook easily. Profile showed him with his wife Monica and twin boys. Happy family photos from Christmas. Made my stomach turn. Instead of going nuclear, I sent Monica a carefully worded message. Hi, Monica. I'm Christina, Mitchell's husband, currently deployed overseas. My daughter mentioned Steven stops by our house Wednesday evenings for book club with my wife. Just wanted to check if you knew about this arrangement. Thanks. Monica responded within an hour. What book club? Steven told me he has faculty meetings every Wednesday until late. Gets home around 10 p m. I had no idea he was at your house. Bingo. We moved to a phone call. Monica was sharp. Ask the right questions. How long had this been going on? What exactly did my daughter see? I told her everything Charlotte had shared. The overnight car, the coffee mug, the couch situation. Steven's been coming home smelling like women's perfume, Monica said quietly. Said it was from hugging female colleagues goodbye. I felt crazy for thinking. You're not crazy. Trust your instincts. We compared stories. Same lies, same timeline, same bullshit excuses. Monica and I coordinated our approach. I would confront Steven Thursday. I would handle Christina during their next club Thursday evening. Monica Called. I told Steven I knew about Wednesday nights. He broke down immediately, confessed everything. Two months worth. How are you handling it? I'm done. Meeting with a lawyer tomorrow, but I want to catch them first for closure. The following Wednesday, I

What's the worst announcement your school ever made? When I was in my junior year, our principal called an emergency assembly that changed everything. As we filed into the auditorium, I noticed all the teachers had red eyes like they'd been crying. The principal's voice cracked as she announced that our beloved chemistry teacher, Missus Andrews, had terminal brain cancer. She only had three months left. The auditorium erupted in sobs. Missus Andrews wasn't just any teacher. She stayed late helping students with homework, bought supplies for kids who couldn't afford them and made everyone feel special. She refused to stop teaching, saying her students gave her strength. But each week we watched her deteriorate. Her once neat handwriting became shaky. She started forgetting things mid sentence. Sometimes she'd pause during class holding her head in pain. The administration hired a substitute, Mister Parker, to assist her. But we all knew he was really there to take over when she couldn't teach anymore. He stand awkwardly in the back of the room, making everyone uncomfortable. One day, Missus Andrews collapsed during third period. The ambulance came, but she insisted on finishing her lesson from the floor. While waiting, she made us promise to be good for Mister Parker. That was the last time we saw her in person. The school arranged for us to video call her every Friday. At first, she was still herself, cracking jokes from her hospital bed, asking about our weekends. But soon the calls got Shorter, her hair fell out, dark circles formed under her eyes. Our class decided to do something special. We turned our final project into a massive research paper on experimental brain cancer treatments. We worked through lunch breaks and stayed late after school combing through medical journals. Even the bad kids were pulling all nighters doing research. Mister Parker caught us and instead of shutting it down, he helped. He connected us with actual cancer researchers who answered our questions. Our 20 page report grew to 100 pages. We included every promising treatment we could find. The day we finished, we Learned Missus Andrews had slipped into a coma. We sent the report to her husband anyway. He read it to her every day, highlighting different sections. The doctor said even in her coma, her vital signs would improve when he read it. Two weeks later, her husband called the school. He'd shown our report to her oncologist. One of the treatments we'd found, some obscure clinical trial in Finland, was something they hadn't considered. Her doctor made some calls. Missus Andrews got accepted into the trial. The school turned our morning announcements into daily up.

What did your school illegally do? My son Nolan started showing up at home with unexplained bruises. He was 13 and in his first year of special education due to his autism. When I asked him about the marks, I just shut down and start steaming, rubbing his hands together until they were raw. I tried talking to his teachers, but they dismissed my concerns saying he probably got them during his episodes. Nolan hadn't had a meltdown in over two years. Something wasn't adding up. One day while doing laundry, I found dried blood on his shirt collar. That's when I bought a tiny voice recorder and sewed it into his jacket. I know it wasn't legal, but my gut was screaming that something was very wrong. What I heard that night made me physically sick. Special ed teacher Missus Walsh had been locking Nolan in a 4 by 4 foot calm down room, basically a storage closet. Whenever he had trouble focusing, she'd leave him there for hours, sometimes the entire school day. I could hear him crying, begging to be let out, saying he needed to use the bathroom. Missus Walsh would just laugh and tell him to earn his way out by completing worksheets in the dark. The next recording was worse. When Nolan had a panic attack from being confined, two male staff members pinned him face down on the floor. I could hear him struggling to breathe as they pressed their knees into his Back. Maybe this will teach you to behave, one of them said. I stormed into the principal's office the next morning with the recordings. Instead of being horrified, she threatened to have me arrested for illegal surveillance. He even smirked and said no one would believe an unstable child over respected educators. So I went to the school board meeting that night. When it was my turn to speak, I played those recordings on full volume. The room went dead silent except for Nolan's recorded cries. Parents started crying. Board members looked like they were going to be sick. But the district's lawyer jumped in again, threatening legal action against me. They tried ending the meeting early. That's when Thomas Parker, a local news reporter who had a son with autism, stood up. He'd been there doing a story on school funding. I've heard enough, he said, pulling out his phone. This airs tonight at 11 and I've already sent copies to three other stations and the department of education. The school board tried to offer me hush money, $50,000 to handle this privately. I told them they could shove that money where the sun doesn't shine. The story exploded. Other parents came forward with similar recordings. Turns out the calm down room had been used for years. They found scratch marks on the inside of the door from desperate kids trying to get out. Missus Walsh was arrested for child abuse. The principal and three staff members were fired. The district had to pay million.

My boyfriend fell in love with someone else and I couldn't be happier. After his PTSD from Afghanistan left him unable to sleep, his therapist suggested getting a service dog. That's when we met shadow, a military canine who lost his handler in combat. The shelter volunteers told us he'd been found wandering near base, still wearing his tactical vest, searching for the only person he'd ever trusted. The shelter said shadow hadn't eaten properly in weeks. He would stand at attention for hours waiting for commands that would never come. When my boyfriend knelt to greet him, shadow just stared ahead like he was still waiting for his handler to return. My boyfriend later told me he saw himself in those empty eyes, the same thousand yard stare he'd see in the mirror. We brought him home, but shadow wouldn't relax. He patrol the house all night, checking windows, guarding doors, just like my boyfriend. Some nights I find them both awake at 3:00am sitting together in silence, fighting battles only they could see. Then one night during a thunderstorm, my boyfriend had a panic attack. Before I could reach him, shadow pressed against his chest just like he'd been trained. For the first time, both of them let their guard down. They held each other until the storm passed. Two broken soldiers finding strength in each other. Now they heal each other. Shadow sleeps at the foot of our bed instead of guarding it. My boyfriend laughs again. Teaches shadow to play fetch instead of patrol. Yesterday, I watched them napping on the couch, two soldiers finally home from war. Shadow was wearing a new collar. Attached to it was a ring and a question I couldn't wait to answer.

What's the dumbest rule your school ever made? Our high school implemented a no water bottles in class policy my senior year. Administration claimed students were sneaking in alcohol, though there hadn't been a single incident all year. The rule was absurd. Arizona in August regularly hits 110 degrees Fahrenheit and our school's ancient water fountains produced lukewarm trickles at best. Half of them were permanently broken. Athletes were especially impacted. After morning practice, we'd be desperately dehydrated all day. Headaches became normal. A girl in my math class actually fainted during a test. When Marcos, our star basketball player, got sent to detention for having water after practice, our team captain Mia decided enough was enough. Operation Dehydration demonstration began on Monday. Every athletic team showed up with empty transparent water bottles labeled water I'm not allowed to drink. Tuesday, the science club posted medical research about dehydration symptoms on every bulletin board. Administration doubled down, threatening suspensions. That's when our school newspaper published an interview with the district's own athletic trainer who explicitly stated that the policy was dangerous and contradicted basic health guidelines. Wednesday morning, Coach Martinez found Jason, a cross country runner, unconscious after practice. The ambulance diagnosis, severe dehydration. His parents threatened to sue. By Friday, local news vans were parked outside. Parents were calling the district office non stop. Our principal looked physically ill as he made a new announcement. Effective immediately, clear water bottles will be permitted in all classroom.

What is the rudest thing you have experienced while eating dinner at a friend's house? When I was about 10 or 11, my friend Emily invited me over for dinner. Her family was well off. And while my family wasn't poor, we definitely weren't on their level. I called my dad to ask if I could stay, and he said yes, but joked that I'd be missing out because he was making spaghetti and homemade garlic bread that night. Turns out Emily's mom was also making spaghetti and garlic bread. I mentioned it casually and her mom just looked at me and said, you're lying. You can't afford to make something like that. And men don't cook. I've been taught not to talk back to adults, so I just turned away and started playing with their cat. When it was time for dinner, I went to wash my hands. When I came back, everyone was already seated at the table with nice plates, silverware and glasses. But my spot, a paper plate, plastic utensils and a wobbly stool tucked awkwardly at the corner of the table. They had extra chairs, they had extra plate, but they still singled me out. I sat there trying not to feel embarrassed as I ate my dinner off a paper plate. When we finished eating, everyone started clearing their dishes to put them in the dishwasher. I didn't have real dishes, so I just threw my plate and plastic fork away. Then they brought Out ice cream sundaes, but not for me. Apparently, their rule was that you only got dessert if you put your dishes in the dishwasher. I sat there watching everyone eat their sundaes while I stared at my empty spot on the table. By the time my parents came to pick me up, I would.

What made you straight up nope out of a relationship? My girlfriend, Bianca was obsessed with skincare. Her bathroom looked like a Sephora. Hundreds of products lined up on custom shelves. She'd installed glass bottles, Korean serums, French moisturizers. She'd spend two hours every night on her elaborate routine, explaining each step like a beauty guru. I thought it was cute how dedicated she was to self care. Bianca had porcelain skin that literally glowed. She worked as a makeup artist for a local theater company. So I figured her flawless complexion was just professional knowledge paying off until I started breaking out. At first, it was just a few pimples on my forehead. No big deal. I'm 28. But sometimes adult acne happens, right? But then it spread. Weird, painful cysts rupt it all over my face and neck. Deep, angry bumps that hurt to touch. I'd never had acne like this in my entire life, not even as a teenager. Bianca was incredibly sweet about it. She'd examine my face with genuine concern, tracing the inflamed areas with her fingertips. Poor baby. This must be so frustrating for you. She researched online for hours, constantly offering solutions. I think it might be stress related or maybe you're allergic to something new. She bought me special face wash, expensive serums, even booked me an appointment with her dermatologist. The doctor was completely baffled. My hormone levels were normal. No underlying health condition. Sometimes these things just happen, she said. With a shrug, let's try some topical treatments. Nothing worked. If anything, my skin kept getting worse. I looked like a pepperoni pizza. Deep red welts covered my cheeks and jawline. My confidence was completely destroyed. I stopped hanging out with friends, barely wanted to leave the apartment. Even wearing a mask felt pointless because people could still see the inflammation around my eyes. Bianca was my rock through everything. She never made me feel ugly or self conscious. You're still handsome to me, she'd whisper, kissing my forehead gently. We'll figure this out together, I promise. She suggested I start using some of her products. These are gentle, all natural ingredients. They might help calm the irritation. She created a special routine just for me, a cleanser, toner and moisturizer that she and into smaller bottles. But weeks passed and my skin kept deteriorating. The breakouts were so severe that I could barely sleep. My pillowcases were constantly stained with blood and pus. I felt like a monster. One Tuesday morning, Bianca left for work unusually early, some emergency with costumes for opening night. In her rush, she forgot her makeup bag on the bathroom counter. I was grabbing tissues to. I had a particularly nasty cyst when I accidentally knocked her bag over. Product scattered across the tile floor. As I gathered everything up, trying to put items back where they belonged, something caught my eye. A small amber bottle had rolled under the vanity. I picked it. Up and read the label, Comedogenic Oil Blend, Professional Grade for special effects makeup. My stomach dropped. I had no idea what comedogenic meant, but special effects didn't sound good. I pulled out my phone and googled it. Comedogenic ingredients are specifically designed to clog pores and create acne. This particular product was used by makeup artists to create realistic skin problems for movies and television. Fake acne that looked completely real. My hands were shaking as I read review after review from film industry professionals praising how authentic the breakouts looked, how the formula could create everything from mild blemishes to severe cystic acne. I ran to my bathroom and grabbed all the helpful products Bianca had been giving me, the face wash, the toner, the moisturizer she'd so lovingly prepared in those little bottles just for me. I compared the ingredients. Every single product Bianca had given me contained calm.

You refuse to split the dinner Bill after ordering the most expensive items. So my coworker Jake always did this thing at our weekly team lunches. He'd order like he was feeding a family of five, then suggest we split the whole Bill to keep things simple. This has been going on for months. Every Friday, same routine. Jake would get multiple appetizers, the most expensive entree, extra sides, dessert, and at least two drinks. The rest of us would order normal portions and end up subsidizing his feast. We all complained about it in our group chat, but nobody ever called him out face to face because he was technically senior to most of us, and we didn't want workplace drama. Last Tuesday was different, though. Our manager, Steve, took the whole sales team to this upscale steakhouse downtown to celebrate closing our biggest deal of the quarter. There were eight of us total, including a couple new hires who'd never experienced Jake's dining habits. The restaurant was fancy. White tablecloths, leather menus, the kind of place where water comes in wine glasses. Steve told us to order whatever we wanted. Since the company was covering lunch as a Celebration, everyone started ordering pretty reasonably. I got a chicken Caesar salad for $18. Most people went for burgers or pasta dishes in the 22 to 25 range. Sarah from accounting got the fish tacos. The new guy, Marcus or, ordered a club sandwich and seemed worried even about that. But Jake. Oh, man. Jake saw this as his moment. First, he orders the Tomahawk ribeye, the 65 one that serves two people. Then he adds the lobster Mac and cheese as his side for another 24. Before anyone can even process that, he's telling the server, let's start the table off with your deluxe seafood tower, a forty five dollar appetizer that nobody asked for. I'm watching the server write all this down while everyone else just stares. The new hires look like they're calculating their rent money in their heads. Throughout lunch, Jake keeps ordering two craft cocktails at fourteen dollars each, a side of truffle fries. He even gets dessert. Some sixteen dollar chocolate thing with gold eggs on it. The whole time he's talking about his big commission check that just cleared. How he's looking at new cars, maybe taking a vacation to Europe, really laying it on thick about his recent financial success. When the server brings the check, Jake immediately snatches it up before Steve can even reach for it. Whoa, guys, this is more than I expected, he says, doing his fake concerned math face. Looks like we're at about $85 each with tip. Not too bad for a place like this though, right? I watch the color drain from Marcus's face. Sarah starts nerve, seriously checking her phone. Everyone's doing that thing where they suddenly become very interested in their water glasses because nobody wants to be the one to object. That's When something clicked in my brain, Jake had literally spent the entire morning bragging about his commission bonus. He'd been showing people his bank account balance on his phone. He'd made jokes about buying rounds of drinks later. So I stood up, smiled real big, and said, you know what, Jake? Since you've been celebrating that huge commission check all morning, and since you were just telling us about how well you're doing financially, why don't you pick up the whole tab for the team? We'd really appreciate the job. The entire table went dead silent. Every head turned to look at Jake like they were watching a tennis match. I could see the panic in his eyes. Our manager, Steve, raised an eyebrow and leaned back in his chair with this little smirk, clearly interested to see how this would lay out. Jake's face went from normal

You ever watch someone dig their own grave and just let them? My sister Miranda thought she was getting our grandma's house when she died. For two years, she played the perfect granddaughter, visiting every day, cooking meals, posting about what an angel she was on social media. Meanwhile, I'm the disappointment who only calls twice a week because as I work double shifts at the warehouse to pay rent on my crappy studio apartment. It started right after grandma's stroke. Miranda swooped in like some kind of savior, suddenly appearing at every doctor's appointment with her leather planner and designer purse. She'd moved back from Seattle claiming she wanted to be there for family during this difficult time. At Sunday dinners, Miranda would sit right next to grandma, cutting her food and speaking loudly like she was deaf. Grandma, you know I take such good care of your beautiful house. Some people are just too busy with their own lives to appreciate what really matters. She'd shoot me these pointed looks across the table while I sat there in my work uniform, exhausted from pulling overtime. Miranda had quit her marketing job, claiming she needed to focus on family caregiving. Real noble. Except she was living rent free in grandma's guest room while I was breaking my back just to survive. The social media posts were the worst part. Every day, Miranda would upload photos of herself spoon feeding grandma soup or reading to her with captions like less To spend time with my sweet grandmother and family is everything. The comments poured in, praising what a wonderful granddaughter she was. Miranda even convinced grandma to let her help organize finances and paperwork. She'd wave around power of attorney documents, making sure everyone knew she was the responsible one handling Grandma's affairs. What Miranda didn't know was that grandma saw right through every calculated move. Three months ago, grandma called me over on a Tuesday evening. Miranda was at her book club, the one she joined specifically because, as it met at the country club where rich widows gathered, grandma pulled out a vanilla envelope from her Kitley drawer. Your sister thinks kindness can be performed for an audience, she said, tapping the envelope. But you've been quietly slipping me grocery money for three years, haven't you? My stomach dropped. I've been leaving cash in her cookie jar whenever I visited, never saying anything because I knew she was too proud to accept help directly. Somehow she'd figured it out. You never posted about it, never asked for, never expected anything in return. Her eyes were sharp. Despite her age. Miranda documents every glass of water she brings me. But you've been making sure I could afford my medications without anyone knowing. She opened the envelope and showed me two copies of her will. One was dated six months ago. The fake one Miranda had been sneaking peaks at when she thought no one was looking. It left Miranda The house and most assets. The other was dated last week. I've been testing you both, grandma said. Every time Miranda post those photos about being the devoted granddaughter, I document what she's really after. She asked me 12 times about updating my will. 12 times, Eddie. Grandma had been playing chess while Miranda thought she was playing checkers. When grandma passed last week, Miranda was devastated, but not in the way you'd expect from someone losing a loved one. At the funeral, she kept whispering to relatives about handling the estate and making sure Grandma's wishes are honored. Yesterday, we all gathered at the lawyer's office. Miranda strutted in, wearing all black designer clothes, clutching tissues for show. She positioned herself in the chair closest to the lawyer, pulling out her phone to record for family records. So lawyer Mister Lee cleared his throat and began reading. I, Edith Sullivan, being of sound mind and body, do hereby bequeath the following. Miranda sat forward, practically vibrating with anticipation. To my granddaughter, Miranda, who cared so much about how things appeared to others. I leave my collection of photo albums and scrapbook.

When did your in laws stop treating you like a gold digger? My boyfriend's parents still make me eat in the kitchen when I visit their house. Not joking. His mother, Rosalind, literally sets up a food tray by the dishwasher while the family eats in the dining room. This all started when they saw one photo of me in hospital scrubs and decided I was a gold digger trying to marry their trust fund son for money. Reggie, his father, slides me twenty dollar bills after dinner for my lunch money. Roslyn asked me to wash my hands twice before touching anything, since nurses are always dirty. My boyfriend just smiles and lets them talk. He knows I love a good verbal sparring match, and more importantly, he knows the truth about what I actually do at that hospital. Last month at their annual family reunion, I found out just how little they thought of me. At Thanksgiving dinner, my sister stood up and announced, we voted, and you're not family anymore. Everyone cheered. I laughed softly and said, then I guess you won't need this. I placed a folder on the table. The moment she opened it, she started screaming. Before we carve the Turkey, Natalie said, rising with that rehearsed smile, there's something we need to say. The room went silent. We had a family vote. You're not family anymore! Cheering. Actual cheering. My cousin Laura clapped like she was at a concert. Uncle Ben raised his wine glass. Even my mother laughed and said, well, someone had to say it. My dad just sipped his beer and muttered, it's probably for the best. Wow, I said, pushing back slowly. You rehearse this? Natalie grinned wider. You've been toxic for years. We're done pretending. It's unanimous, my mother added. I looked around. No one spoke up. Good, I said quietly, reaching into my bag. I figured this might happen. I pulled out a thick folder and placed it in the center. The heavy thought of it hitting the table cut through the laughter. Natalie blinked. What is that? I smiled and folded my arms. Why don't you find out? She snatched it and ripped it open, that snide smirk forming. Then she turned the first page and stopped smiling. Her face went pale. Then she screamed. Blood curdling horror movie scream. Her chair crashed behind her as she bolted upright, slamming the folder shut. You monster! She cried. You messed up freak! Joel! Her husband grabbed the folder. His jaw dropped. Is this. I nodded once. It's all real. Every word, every receipt, every screenshot. Dead silence. You were so sure I wouldn't fight back, I said, standing slowly, so sure I'd stay the quiet one. The doormat. The cash cow. Let me tell you what was in that folder. Five years of records. Over $78,000 sent to family members, all documented. $8,000 for Joel's rehab. Actually a spa retreat. $2,300 for Natalie's emergency dental work, elective veneers. $12,000 for mom's credit card debt. $4,500 for a family emergency. Actually a Cabo trip. Screw. Screenshots of Natalie calling me a cash cow with no spine, posts where they mocked me, texts where she called me manipulative for refusing to co sign her business loan. And the cherry on top, hotel receipts showing Natalie spent three nights in Santa Monica with someone named Alyssa, charged to Joel's credit card. That's what made her scream. She wasn't just exposed, she. It was dismantled, fact by fact. Joel flipped through pages, his face paling. What's this about Santa Monica? Who's Alyssa? Why were you at a hotel for three nights on my credit card? Silence. Let's be reasonable. My mom tried. Sure, I said. Let's talk about when you called me a parasite while cashing my check. We were under stress, she stammered. No, I snapped. You were under stress, and I bailed you out every time. The one time I say no, I'm the enemy. My dad spoke up. You're making this bigger than it is. You let them do this for years. I said, you knew. You saw it. You let it happen because it was easier. You're just bitter because no one needs you anymore. Natalie shouted. Wrong. I said coldly, I'm not bitter. I'm done. You think this

Foster children. What's the most insane thing you ever experienced? When I was 10, I got placed with the lanes. They seemed normal at first. Nice house, good food. Even gave me my own bedroom with cartoon wallpaper. But something felt weird from day one. They never let me go outside alone, not even to the mailbox. If I wanted to play in the backyard, one of them had to watch me through the window. When I asked why, they said it was for my safety. I figured all foster parents were protective like that. At school, if I got any papers or notes, I had to hand them over the second I walked in the door. They said they needed to check everything for my own good. They locked up my backpack at night and went through it while I slept. I thought this was normal, too. The weirdest thing was the computer. I had one in the living room, but I wasn't allowed to touch it. Ever. They said the internet was dangerous for kids. When other kids at school talked about games or videos they saw online, I just. Just nodded along and pretended I knew what they meant. One night, I lost a tooth. I put it under my pillow like always, expecting to wake up to a dollar or some quarters. Instead, I found a tiny folded note written in handwriting I'd never seen before. It said, you're not who they think you are. Check Behind the mirror, I scared out of my mind. At school the next day, I asked my teacher, Missus Kim, if the tooth fairy ever left notes instead of money. She laughed and said, no, the tooth fairy only brings coins. That made me even more confused. At night, while the lanes were downstairs watching their usual cop shows, I carefully pulled the mirror off my bedroom wall. My hands were shaking the whole time. Behind it was a small hole cut into the wall, and inside was a plastic bag stuffed with papers. I pulled everything out. Birth certificates, newspaper clippings, photos of kids who looked like me but weren't me. One photo showed a little girl with my exact eyes but different hair. Another showed a teenager who could have been my sister. Then I found the missing child flyer. It had a picture of a six year old girl named Sophie Blanchard, missing for four years. The girl in the photo looked exactly like me, just younger. My stomach dropped to the floor. There were handwritten notes, too. They rename all the kids. Tell someone the truth. Call Aunt Jane. She's still looking. I spent the next week acting totally normal, eating dinner and doing homework like nothing happened. But inside, I was freaking out. During lunch at school, I snuck into the classroom and use the phone to call the number written on one of the papers. A woman answered, and when I said the name Sophie Blanchard. She started crying so hard I could barely understand her. She kept asking where I was, if I was safe, if I remembered her. I hung up because I got scared. That weekend, two people from child services showed up at our door without warning. The lanes tried to act calm, saying it must be some kind of mistake. But the officers found more hidden files in the attic.

How did the worst misunderstanding of your life lead to meeting your spouse? The building manager knocked on my door at 6 a m. Sir, open up or we'll call the police. My neighbour hid behind him, carefully holding a binder labelled evidence. The manager cleared his throat. Sir, we need to discuss some serious allegations. We've received complaints of your stalking behaviour. Would you mind letting us in? I was surprised. Stalking? No, I'm sure this is all just a funny misunderstanding. I said. Thank. What could I have even done that felt like stalking? Then let us in, he insisted coldly. They walked in and immediately started looking around. My neighbor pointed at my balcony. That's where he watches me every morning. Look, there's even a notebook. She grabbed it before I could react and started reading out loud. 5:00am, she left, crying. 602:00am, she came back. 7:00am, she looked tired, didn't eat breakfast. Her hands started shaking in fear. The manager frowned. You're documenting her routine? I shook my head. No. Well, yes, but it's because this goes back three months. Every single day. She gasped, covering her mouth. My neighbor spotted my phone on the counter. Stay right where you are. Passcode now, he said, radioing security in case things went south. 2,352, I told. They opened up my gallery and scrolled through the dozens of pictures from the park. She was in every single one. Oh, my god, she said, showing the manager. He's been Photographing me everywhere I go. The manager's expression darkened. Okay, I know this looks bad, but please let me explain. I begged, but my neighbor refused, pulling out more evidence. Text messages from her friends. Look, he followed me to the pet store last week. My friend saw him hiding behind the dog food aisle. The manager studied the photos. He always asked me weird questions, too. He's like, are you going anywhere overnight this weekend? And stuff. Like, why would you need to know that? voice_to_text: The man is cursing god, but the next moment god sends him a text message. He thought it was a scam, so he put it back in his pocket. The next day, god sends him another message. He threw the pager out the window in anger. But a few hours later, he took the dog out for a pee, didn't expect the broken pager to still be ringing like crazy. Out of curiosity, he returned the call, but the guy on the other end said he had a surprise for him. The next day, Bruce went to the address he gave him and arrived at an office building. But as soon as he got out of the car, he accidentally stepped in a puddle. Once again, he cursed god in anger and then he went inside the building and there was only one cleaner. He felt he had been tricked, so he wanted to leave the cleaner behind. Him suddenly took off his uniform to reveal an exquisite and luxurious suit and he said Bruce's name and all his background. The man explained that he knew everything about Bruce because his whole life was recorded in this cabinet. Bruce half heartedly tried to look in the cabinet, but he didn't notice that god took a few steps back. The next second, the cabinet opens at the speed of light. It dragged Bruce to the other side. God pulls out his dossier and then he knocked on the cabinet and the Cabinet retracted quickly. Bruce was very puzzled. He couldn't help but ask who he was, and he calmly says, he's God. Bruce thought he was full of shit, so he decided to test him. He put his hand behind his back and asked the old man to guess how many fingers he was holding out. God guessed the correct answer in a flash. But Bruce started to cheat. He snuck one of his fingers back. Aha! But he still didn't believe the old man was god. He thought it was all a coincidence. And that's when god said he was going on vacation. He wanted Bruce to take over as god for a few days, and during that time, he would have all his powers. But the unlucky Bruce just thought the old man might be crazy. He got scared and left the place. But then a series of strange things happened.

voice_to_text: 10 months pregnant and Polaris, she's not your average mom to be. Sorry, maybe just kicking. She's Magneto's daughter. Yeah, that Magneto, the guy who can bend steel like it's paper. And she's inherited every bit of that terrifying power. Her name alone makes anti mutant groups lose sleep. If her emotions snap, every scrap of metal around her turns into a weapon. That's why her bodyguard isn't just anyone. It's Esme, a mutant who can handle herself in any fight. Night falls, lights start flickering. Polaris grabs her stomach, nearly buckling over. Everyone rushes her into a custom built delivery room reinforced like a weapon's fault. But then her powers flare. Even the heavy duty forklift outside starts inching toward her. The boss strips off every piece of metal he's wearing, terrified the whole building's about to collapse. Meanwhile, the baby's father feels something's wrong from outside. He sees the lights flashing like a distress signal. Inside, it's chaos. With every scream, metal objects rip through the air like they're possessed. Polaris's breathing gets ragged. She's fading fast. The doctor whispers to Esme. If they don't act now, both mom and baby are done for. In comes the psychic triplets. One locks eyes with Polaris, flooding her mind with a vision, a future where mutants live free and her child grows up in peace. Just like that, Polaris's will to fight surges back. Her friends cheer her on. The doctor shouts for one last push. She lets out a Roar and boom, street lights explode, power poles snap, the whole city goes dark. And all this just for one baby's arrival. Finally, the cry of a Newborn cuts through the silence. Polaris looks down at her daughter, Dawn. She whispers, that's her name. But the joy doesn't last long. In the elevator, she hears one of the psychics humming a lullaby, her lullaby, the one only she's sung to her baby, which means that psychics been inside her daughter's mind. Polaris's eyes narrow, rage boiling until Esme steps in, shutting it down before it gets ugly. Not long after, Polaris is back in action, heading out on a mission to rescue a mutant girl named Becky. Because no matter how powerful she is, she knows some battles aren't just about strength.

voice_to_text: To escape from killers pursuing him, a man hid inside a wardrobe. But when he opened the wardrobe, he was horrified to discover he had somehow ended up in a stranger's home. Just as the man was about to leave, he heard voices coming from outside. In this critical moment, the panicked man could only immediately hide under the bed. What he didn't expect was that from the homeowner's conversation, he Learned of an opportunity that would change his fate. They weren't planning to use this antique wardrobe. This gave the man being hunted by killers a reason to stay. Only after the male and female homeowners fell asleep did he quietly crawl out from under the bed. Needing to urinate urgently, Jack rushed to the bathroom. But he realized urinating in the toilet would make noise. So Jack went to the sink to solve his urgent problem. Then he returned under the bed to simply get through the night. The next morning, Jack waited until everyone had left the house before slowly crawling out from under the bed. He went to the refrigerator and took out milk and cookies, then enjoyed eating breakfast at the table. After eating, he even washed all the used dishes clean. Then he changed into sports wear. voice_to_text: Never seen a postman work so hard to deliver an 800 mile express letter as quickly as possible. He treated himself like a relay baton, passing himself between horses. As soon as the little horse got the postman, it switch to high gear. Speed instantly shot up to 370 and even steep, dangerous cliffs felt like flat ground. As the ace of the postal world, the man's goal was always to deliver the letter as fast as possible. But there was one thing that limited his speed, the stamina of the horse under him. So whenever the horse started slowing down, he would contact the post office ahead of him to prepare a new horse. When they heard the ace postman was on his way, a rookie horse immediately volunteered. Though inexperienced, he had a passion for the Postal Service. Seeing the little horse so eager, the boss couldn't wait to approve him. After a few friendly words of advice, the little horse, full of energy, went to the roadside, warming up and getting into the zone. Now starting the ninth set of calisthenics. March in place. 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8. 2, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7. Stop! At that moment, the postman's old horse, eager to clock out, saw the little horse and quickly handed the man over like a baton. The little horse grabbed him and pressed him against his back, activating turbo mode and shooting off. Experienced old horses watching this couldn't Help but smirk. The little horse, fresh to the job, was fearless and reckless, speeding insanely fast. But he was distracted, not watching the road, and both he and the postman plunged off a cliff. Luckily, a pond below softened their fall. More fortunately, they had two and a half years of breath holding training. But the bad luck didn't stop there. Just as they resurfaced, they fell into an even deeper pool. As bubbles floated to the surface, the postman's greeting to the little horse was definitely full of gold. The little horse, thoroughly dejected, lay motionless. The engine waterlogged, but the postman had a few slick tricks up his sleeve. Fully revived, the little horse was back on his hooves, running like a beast. Until a sudden emergency break flung the postman off the cliff. He slid for five or six hundred meters before realizing something was wrong. But he stayed calm, performed an emergency stop, and spun around, riding the air back toward the little horse. One had to wonder if he and Newton shared some sort of mysterious connection. But just when things seemed to settle, the postman found himself in trouble again. The infamous bandit Jiang Yang was now on his tail. Rumor had it this Bandit could make even the mighty Nezza leave behind three pounds of lotus powder. Before robbing anyone, he had to apply sunscreen. He was a beauty fanatic, after all. Despite his small stature of only half a meter, his Horse under him was no slouch. The height of two and a half meters, he looked down on every preschooler. The postman sensed danger and quickly turned. He saw the bandit closing in fast, so he slammed the brakes, using the little horse's cover to prepare for a one on one showdown. But the little horse, realising something was off, bolted behind the postman. No matter what the man commanded, he just wouldn't listen. After all, he was just a horse. The man gave up trying to order him around and decided to use reason. Fists are the real answer. A saying that proved true. But before he could fight back, he locked eyes with the bandit, awkwardly smiling and politely nodding. Then he turned and ran. The little horse, now fully awake, followed closely. To their surprise, they reached a perfect synchronization, racing together powerfully, shaking off the bandit and charging into the final station. The Bandit, now headed straight for the iron gate, slammed on the brakes in panic, throwing out a two room apartment in the process. Finally, the postman delivered the letter. But just as he did, he was stunned to see a little elf pop out of the bag.

Found my son's homework where he had to describe me at work. He wrote that I rob banks and hide the money under the floorboards. I was helping my eight year old Rowan with his backpack when I found his. My parents job worksheets stuff. Between his math homework and a crumpled juice box. In his messy second grade handwriting, he'd written, my daddy robs banks everyday, brings home lots of money and puts it under our kitchen floor. Sometimes he counts it at night when Mommy's sleeping and they whisper about numbers. At first I laughed it off. Kids say the weirdest things, right? I work as an armored truck driver for Brink Security. Technically, I do go to banks every day and handle massive amounts of cash. probably just got confused about what daddy actually does for work. But then his teacher called Tuesday morning. Mr Whitaker, we need to talk about Rowan's assignment. He's been telling his classmates some very detailed stories about your financial activities. Yesterday during show and tell, he described exactly how you open bank vaults and mentioned specific dollar amounts. Stomach dropped. Missus Aldridge, I drive an armored truck. I transport money legally. Rowan must be misunderstanding what he sees. He also drew a picture of your house with an X marking where the money is hidden. The other children are asking their parents why their dads don't bring home bank money, too. I left work early, my mind racing. How could Rowan know specific details about bank procedure?

When did helicopter parenting almost cost everything? I was on Facetime at 1:00am with my girlfriend when my mom burst through my door without knocking, finding me mid laugh with Nadine on my phone screen. Are you serious right now? Mom shrieked, grabbing my phone while Nadine's confused face disappeared into darkness. This is completely inappropriate. It's a school night. Dad appeared behind her, shaking his head like I committed some federal crime. They didn't care that I had straight A's, that this was my chance with my crush, or that these late night calls were the only thing keeping her interested in me. You're 16. You don't need to be talking to girls at all hours. It was insane. Complete device lockdown after 9 p m. Phone physically placed in their bedroom every night. Wi-Fi router programmed to kill my connection. Even my laptop taken away just in case. Mom installed one of those parental control apps that sent her alerts if I even touched any device after curfew. Healthy boundaries, she kept saying, showing me some article about teenage sleep schedule she'd found on Facebook. That first night without talking to Nadine was torture. I lay in bed staring at the ceiling, wondering if she thought I was ignoring her, if she was upset, if she think I didn't care anymore. My parents did three separate checks that night, opening my door to make sure I was in bed, sleep device less, and alone. The second night, I Couldn't handle it. Nadine had texted me 17 times during school asking if I was okay if we were breaking up. Then I got an idea. I remembered my iPhone 6 buried in my closet. Cracked screen, terrible battery. But it could work. After my parents 9:30 p m. Check, I waited until 10:15 to be safe, then pulled out the hidden phone. Nadine's face appeared, pixelated and laggy, but she was smiling. I thought your parents murdered you, she whispered, and I had to bite my tongue to keep from laughing. We developed an intricate system based on my parents patterns. Mom always did checks throughout the night. I became a master of deception. The moment I heard her footsteps on the stairs. I'd whisper, she's coming to Nadine, kill the screen, slide the phone under my pillow, close my eyes, and control every micro expression on my face. The hardest part was when mom would just stand there staring, and I'd have to remain completely stone faced, breathing steady and deep, like I was truly asleep. Once mom actually walked over and stood directly over me for a full minute. It was torture. Then, weirdly, Nadine asked me, babe, are you okay? You keep coughing. I hadn't even noticed I was doing it, but she was right. My throat felt scratchy and weird. Maybe you're getting sick, she suggested. But. And I smelled it. Something sharp and chemical cutting through my room. Hold on, I whispered. And when I opened my bedroom door. My stomach dropped. Gray smoke was flowing along the hallway ceiling like a river, getting thicker by the second, pouring from the direct

The bullies thought I was still their scrawny punching bag. Wait until they see what a year in China taught me. I start seventh grade with a renewed boost of confidence after spending a year with my grandparents in China. Walking into the school, I spot my worst nightmare. I knew this moment would come eventually. There's Shane, still the same 5 feet 8 inches tower of teenage cruelty, flanked by his usual suspects, Minion 1 and Minion 2. Such loyal followers. I'm still only 5 feet 2 inches and probably look exactly the same to them. Same. See? Brown hair, same hand me down clothes, same kid they used to stuff into lockers every Tuesday. Like clockwork. Well, well, well, look who's back, Shane announces loud enough for half the hallway to hear. We missed our little toilet bowl cleaner. Minion one actually claps his hands together like he's genuinely excited. Dude, remember when we made him eat that sandwich off the bathroom floor? They're laughing about it like it's their fondest memory. And I feel that familiar burning in my chest. Except this time it feels different. Controlled. My grandfather's voice echoes in my head. Anger is fire. You can let it burn you, or you can forge steel with it. Minion two steps closer, invading my personal space. Hope you didn't get too comfortable wherever you went, because nothing's changed here. He shoves my shoulder, testing to see if I'll react the same way I used to. Cowering and apologizing instead, I steady myself and look him directly in the eye. Everything's changed, I say quietly, but Minion 2 just laughs and walks away with his friends. Same scared little mouse. Shane calls over his shoulder. See you in P E. Bathroom, boy. P E. Class arrives like a death sentence, and of course coach pairs us up for defensive exercises, which basically his excuse to let kids beat each other up legally. Shane immediately volunteers to be my partner, grinning like Christmas morning. This is going to be fun! He tells Minion 1 and Minion 2, who are partnered nearby. I've been saving up a year's worth of frustration. He starts small, an accidental elbow to my ribs during warm UPS. Oops! Sorry Mouse Boy, didn't mean to hurt you. When I tell him I'm not weak anymore, he literally doubles over laughing. Not weak? You're the same 70 pound scarecrow who cried when I gave you a wedgie! That's when he crosses the line. During partner exercises, he's supposed to hold the punching pad steady, but instead he keeps jerking it away so my punches miss and I stumble forward. Maybe if you ate some actual food instead of whatever they feed mice. The rage is building in my chest, but I hear Grandpa's training. The river that moves mountains doesn't rage. It flows with purpose. Coach steps away to help another student with their form, and that's when Shane decides to get Creative. Minion 1 comes and hands Shane a bucket, which he dumps over my head. Water splashes down, soaking my clothes. Here you go, mouse boy, you looked a bit thirsty. Minion 1 and Minion 2 are recording with their phones now, probably planning to post it on social media. I'm dripping wet and Shane gets in my face, but still I hold back. Then he spots my friend Jace across the gym and smiles. Shane's now

I blew up at my husband for lying to me about my sister and her baby leaving when he actually kicked her out. My sister Maya had just escaped the worst relationship of her life. She moved in with me and my husband Kyle, bringing her five month old son, Oliver. She was dealing with postpartum depression and regular depression on top of everything else. Kyle said absolutely when I asked if she could stay with us. Actually, he was the one who drove three hours to pick them up. For two weeks, everything seemed fine. Maya helped with dishes and laundry without me even asking. But then Kyle started complaining about Oliver crying at night. I mean, what did he expect from a five month old baby? Suggested he wear earbuds to sleep, but he just grumbled and said, forget it. Last week I had to drive four hours away for my friend Jessica's funeral. Kyle said he'd stay home to keep an eye on Maya and make sure she was okay. I thought that was sweet of him, honestly. When I got back the next day, the house was completely silent. No baby sounds, no Maya humming while she folded clothes like she always did. I called out for them, but got nothing. Kyle came downstairs looking weird, kind of nervous, but trying to act casual. He told me Maya had called some friend in another town and decided to move there. That morning, he handed me this. Crumpled letter that supposedly was from her. The whole thing felt wrong. Maya would have called me or at least texted. We talked every day about everything. I called her phone about 20 times. No answer. Kyle said she must have left it behind because he found it on the kitchen counter. That made zero sense. Maya never went anywhere without her phone, especially with a baby. I started calling our relatives. Our Aunt Carol, our cousin Brett, even our grandma, who Maya called every Sunday. Nobody had heard from her. Nobody even knew she was planning to leave. Kyle kept saying she probably just needed space and would call when she was ready. For six days, I barely slept. Kept thinking about Maya. Alone somewhere with Oliver, dealing with her depression without any support. Kyle got annoyed when I kept bringing it up. He said I was being dramatic and that Maya was a grown woman who could take care of herself. Yesterday, my phone rang from a number I didn't recognize. It was Maya, and she was crying. She told me Kyle had kicked her out the day I left for the funeral. He told her she wasn't welcome anymore and needed to take responsibility for her decisions instead of depending on us. She wasn't staying with some friend. She was at a homeless shelter downtown with Oliver. She had no money, no car, nothing.

Have you seen your father? Hello? Is dinner almost ready? Yes. Peter? God, where are you? I can barely hear you. Pull back my chair ever so slightly. Ah! Daddy's home. Will you hold this for daddy? Okay. Why? Uh, it's a present. It's a thanks for being such a sweetie watermelon. So you'll hang on to that? Yeah, sure. Yeah. This is weird. Am I supposed to eat this? I hate you! I hate you! Alright, Chris, Meg loves to listen to music when she sleeps. Let's see how she likes this. Uh, dad, I don't think that's how it works. This had nothing to do with the harmonica.

What did your dad's girlfriend do to earn the title mom? Dinner was painfully awkward. It had been two years since mom left, and my dad's girlfriend, Britt, had tried too hard to impress us, making Dinosaur nuggets and smiley face Mac and cheese like we were five. My brother flipped his plate and glared at her. First you try to take dad away, and now you're bribing us with nuggets? He asked coldly. Colton! Dad yelled. Britt smiled. You're right. Next time I'll add spaghetti, she joked. Table fell silent. Dad coughed awkwardly and stood up to take a call. That's when Brit leaned forward and looked at me and my siblings with a serious expression. Look, I know this is weird, she said. What will it take for you guys to actually like me? My older brother leaned forward, too, eyeing her down, and said in his toughest 13 year old voice, do everything we say for one month. Brit didn't even hesitate. Deal. What's first? What she didn't know was that my brother was already prepared to go to war with her. And what we didn't know was that Brit was prepared, too. My brother announced the first impossible challenge. Best us at every video game we own. I knew he'd start here. Colton was undefeated at Fortnite in our entire school, but Brit showed up the next day, having studied YouTube tutorials all night. She destroyed him five rounds straight, then did the floss dance over His defeated character. My little sister innocently cheered, while my brother insisted it didn't count that he was just warming up. Best of 10, he said, and she won eight out of 10. When my brother looked sad, she showed him the trick she Learned. That way you'll destroy everyone else. He winked. The next challenge was pure physical. Old people can't do obstacle courses. My brother grinned, building one in the backyard with everything from tire runs to rope climbs. But when Brit showed up in full Crossfit gear, we knew we were done for. She ended up beating my brother's record by 30 seconds. Now do it backwards! He demanded. She did it backwards. Now blindfolded. I saw my brother mouth what the heck? When she actually did it blindfolded, using only our shouted directions. Honestly, we were impressed. Is that all you got? She teased. This week you have to pick us up from school instead of dad, but you gotta wear embarrassing costumes. And she did. Turns out Brit was a retired cosplayer. She showed up to school in an Optimus Prime costume, then a fully geared up attack on Titan costume, and a bunch more insane outfits. My friends kept saying, your mom's cool, don't you dare smile! My brother hissed at me. I'm not! I protested. I totally was! The endurance challenge was my brother's last stand, an anime Marathon of one piece to see who could stay awake. My sister fell asleep on Brit's shoulder around our six. Colton and I crashed. After 14 hours, Brit paused the show and covered us all with blankets. She carried my sister to bed and took off her shoes. She tucked me in on the couch, whispering

What's the most awkward love confession you've ever witnessed? My best friend, Trent, paced around the room nervously. What do I do? I think our roommate is in love with me, he muttered. I bursted into laughter. Gemma? I highly doubt it, I said. Our roommates, Gemma and Ali, definitely hadn't shown they were interested in Trent at all. From what I'd seen, Gemma was naturally friendly and Ali was quiet and closed off. But Trent insisted. He pushed a crumpled piece of paper to my chest, laughing, read it and weep. I scanned through the paper that definitely very clearly stated my dazzling Trent, and I was shocked. He was right. Someone had a huge crush on him. Are you sure it's Gemma? I asked. Trent nodded and explained how there had been obvious signs. He offered me coffee when I came over. He said, that's basically asking me out. I reminded him she offered everyone coffee, but she laughed at all my jokes. Then she asked about my weekend plans. That's basically girl code for checking if I'm single, Or she's just asking about your weekend plans like a normal person, I suggested. Then he pulled out actual evidence, a poem on the kitchen counter with romantic lines like brown eyes sweeter than honey and a laugh that makes Monday mornings bearable. That's totally me, he yelled. I shrugged. I don't see it, I joked. He rolled his eyes. And haven't you noticed every time I visit There's always a gift waiting for me. Yeah, I remember that. A box of his favorite brand of herbal tea that no one else drank showed up on his table the day we were out, along with a bookmark with a quote from a movie he mentioned liking and a stress ball that showed up right before his big job interview. Trent had spent weeks building up the courage to talk to Gemma about it, waiting for that one sure sign that Gemma really felt that way about, about him. Then that sign arrived tonight. Trent had stayed late to help me with a project when we heard singing through the walls. One of the girls had been singing Taylor Swift's You Belong With Me in the most angelic voice. Then we heard it. She actually sang his name, adding Trent right into the lyrics. Trent jumped off the couch like he'd been electrocuted. I told you she likes me, he half whispered. He decided right then he was going to confess his feelings. Thanks, too. The next day he showed up at our apartment with a bouquet of roses and a poem he wrote on his own. Trent nervously walked over to Gemma, who was chilling on the couch watching Netflix. He looked up at the flowers and smiled. Wow, nice flowers. You look great, she said, calm and friendly like always. Trent cleared his throat. I know about the poems and the gifts and the song. Gemma's smile. Turned into confusion. Trent, what is this? What's going on? Gemma stared at Trent for a long moment. Wait, are you talking?

When did a teacher attempt to avoid work create 10 times more problems? After telling us that she had mandatory district training for three days starting Monday, my English teacher pointed at me and announced, you'll be teaching the Shakespeare unit while I'm gone since you actually understand the material, unlike everyone else who thinks the movie counts as reading. I stared at her in complete disbelief. Shouldn't we have a substitute teacher? Sure, for this? She shuffled papers, avoiding eye contact because she definitely knew this was wrong. Substitutes are incompetent and I don't have time to train someone on my specific curriculum. I pushed back immediately, but I'm not trained either, and I'm literally a student. She was already halfway out the door, clutching her tote bag. Just follow the lesson plan and make them understand Romeo and Juliet, since there's a test when I get back, have a great weekend. Goodbye. She practically ran from the room before I could protest further. And suddenly I understood exactly how badly this would backfire. Monday morning, I walked into class dragging a suitcase full of zombie makeup and fake blood. We're doing Romeo and Juliet Love in the time of zombies where the Montagues are zombie hunters and the Capulet are secretly infected. Jackson volunteered for Romeo and I told him his character collected zombie teeth as trophies. Sophia got Juliet, who was slowly turning but fighting it for love. We rewrote the balcony scene at the quarantine breach. But soft what light or yonder window breaks, it is the east and Juliet hasn't eaten anyone yet. Jackson delivered while Sophia not on her own arm. For practice, the nurse became a scientist and Friar Lawrence ran an underground zombie shelter. By lunch, everyone had memorized more Shakespeare then they had all semester. Tuesday we created hazmat suits from garbage bags for the Montagues and painted decay on the capsules with whiteout and permanent markers. The party scene became Romeo discovering Juliet wasn't quite human when she tried to bite him during their first kiss. She literally tried to eat your face and you're still into her, someone shouted as Mercutio, who believed the government created the virus. Love conquers all, even the undead, Jackson replied, while Sophia perfected her zombie twitch by watching possum videos. The janitor walked in and saw 30 students covered in fake blood, staging what looked like a biohazard event and immediately left, muttering about his paycheck. Wednesday got completely out of control when I invited other classes to watch without permission. The fight scene turned into Mercurio getting infected while Romeo had to decide whether to kill his best friend before he turned. We used pool noodles as weapons and ketchup packets for blood, which exploded everywhere, coating walls and ceiling and red slatter. A plague on both your houses became. I'm literally plagued by both your houses and it's highly contagious. While the infected Mercurio chased students down the hallway, moaning about Government conspiracies and demanding brains. The cafeteria staff locked their doors when they saw him coming and someone pulled the fire alarm thinking there was an actual emergency happening. The principal arrived after getting six emergency calls about a possible biohazard in the English wing. Plus reports that student.

I was shocked. I thought, is this for real? Denise Holland is making her message explicitly clear. If they have to go to the bathroom, let him go to the bathroom. No one should curb her stepson's bathroom breaks. It's preposterous. You think it's a joke? She says his first grade teacher sent this note home with students at C C. Rono Elementary School last week. It asked parents to encourage bladder endurance so kids only have to use the restroom once or twice in a school day. For children, it's normal for them to go up to 10 to 12 times a day. Pediatric urologist Doctor Jessica T. Casey tells me, waiting too long can cause infections, bed wetting, and even long term kidney damage. We can't be there in the classroom with them.
